<HEADLINE> Expenditures Increased in Saudi New Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has decided
to increase expenditures by 15 billion Riyals (about 4 billion
U.S. dollars) in its 1998 budget, bringing the total expenses to
196 billion Riyals (52.27 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the Kuwaiti News Agency, the Saudi cabinet Monday
endorsed the budget for the new fiscal year starting from January
1 at a meeting chaired by Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The new budget includes a deficit of 18 billion Riyals (4.8
billion dollars), 1.12 billion Riyals (300 million dollars) more
than that in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new budget has allocated 18.98 (5.06 billion dollars) for
social security and aid as well as new projects including schools,
colleges, water ventures, dams, sewage and electrical networks.
But the spending plan did not disclose the country's defense
expenditures which is believed to be a major item in the budget.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi government has hoped to have a revenue of 178 billion
Riyals (47.4 billion dollars) in 1998, compared to the expected
163.88 Riyals (43.7 billion dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that the 1998 budget mirrors the optimism of
the Saudi government about better economic performances in the
coming year, especially in its oil industry.
</P>
<P>
The oil-rich Gulf kingdom has achieved an average of 3.8
percent growth rate of economy in the last three consecutive years
with a peak of 4.3 percent in 1996. Continued growth is also
expected for this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
