<HEADLINE> Rabbani for Peaceful Settlement of Afghan Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The ousted Afghan President,
Burhanuddin Rabbani, stressed on Tuesday that the Afghan issue
could not be solved through military means.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Peshawar, capital of the North
West Frontier Province, Rabbani said that the military options
have to be given up for the amicable settlement of the Afghan
issue.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani, who is currently on a visit to Pakistan at the
invitation of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, said that "peace in
Afghanistan can only be brought through negotiations between the
warring factions."
</P>
<P>
he welcomed the peace initiatives taken by the Pakistani
government for the peaceful settlement of the Afghan imbroglio.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani described his visit to Pakistan as "highly successful."
</P>
<P>
"The trip would help remove misunderstandings between the
Northern Alliance and Pakistan," Rabbani was quoted by the
Associated Press of Pakistan as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani said that his talks with Sharif were satisfactory and
expressed his confidence that these would yield positive results.
</P>
<P>
"I am on a peace mission in order to put an end to the ongoing
war in Afghanistan and to create an atmosphere that could help
establish a government acceptable to all the people of that
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
As a first step, he proposed a permanent ceasefire between
Taliban and the Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani, who is the leader of the anti-Taliban Northern
Alliance, said that he had already expressed his willingness to
hold negotiations with Taliban leaders and added that now the ball
was in the court of Taliban.
</P>
<P>
"Let's see and wait for Taliban reaction over the peace
efforts", he added.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani also said that "we are totally against foreign
interference in the internal affairs of Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
In reply to a question, Rabbani said, "we have launched our
peace efforts and hoped that Taliban would response positively."
</P>
<P>
He denied any difference in the ranks of the Northern Alliance,
saying that there is complete agreement among the members of the
alliance on basic policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
