<HEADLINE> Murders Down in 10 Largest U.S. Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Murders in the 10 largest
cities in the United States are down nearly 10 percent overall
from 1996, which saw 4,600 people slain, local media reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Leading the way are New York and Los Angeles, the two largest
cities in the country, the news reports said.
</P>
<P>
Homicides also were down in Chicago, New Orleans, Dallas,
Houston, Baltimore, San Francisco and Newark in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
However, Denver, Detroit and Nashville saw a sudden rise in
slayings, but statistics by Federal Bureau of Investigation show
serious crime has been decreasing nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Homicides sank to a 30-year low in New York, and plummeted 20
percent in Los Angeles this year to the lowest level since 1977.
There were 566 homicides in the city as of December 14, 143 fewer
than for all of 1996. The city hasn't had fewer than 600 homicides
since 1977, when 574 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
As of Sunday, New York City's death toll stood at 756, down
from 961 a year ago and the lowest level since 1967. New York's
homicide total peaked in 1992 with 2,262 killings.
</P>
<P>
Dallas and Houston reported murder rates that have dropped by
more than half from 1991.
</P>
<P>
Other cities with lower numbers than last year were Chicago,
Newark, Minneapolis, Baltimore, New Orleans, Memphis, and San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
Detroit was the only city in the top ten to show an increase of
killings over 1996. The nation's 10th-largest city reversed a
five-year decline in homicides this year with the death toll
rising to 454 after 428 murders in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Nashville already has a record 112 homicides, compared with 89
in 1996. Homicides were also up in Denver, with 76 murders up to
Sunday this year compared with 68 through December 28 last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
