<HEADLINE> BT Woos Customers With International Calls Discounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- British Telecom today announced
price cuts of 15 per cent for international calls made by many
business customers, in the latest bid to stem the erosion of
overseas call customers.
</P>
<P>
A new tariff package will be launched on January 1,1998, giving
15 per cent discounts on existing prices paid by companies for
calls to 10 nominated destinations.
</P>
<P>
The scheme, called BT Key Countries, applies to businesses
paying between 1000 pounds (1600 U.S. dollars) and 10000 pounds
(16000 U.S. dollars) a quarter for calls, though BT said numbers
eligible to take part were "commercially confidential".
</P>
<P>
The reductions would cut the lowest possible price of a call to
the U.S. to 11.5p (18.4 U.S. cents) a minute, compared with a
standard tariff price of 20.1p (32.2 U.S. cents).
</P>
<P>
The move means BT has in effect abandoned quoting a standard
tariff price for corporate customers after losing business to new
rivals such as Colt and Esprit.
</P>
<P>
BT has been increasingly concerned at price comparison made by
competitors against its standard tariff, which excludes the many
discount packages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
