<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Assuced of Arms Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today accused the military
junta in Sierre Leone of breaching the peace accord by bringing
fighter aircraft into S.Leone.
</P>
<P>
Citing intelligence from Sierra Leone, defense spokesman
Godwin Ugbo said the junta is also developing air fields in some
villages to accommodate the fighters.
</P>
<P>
As the main airport in Lungi is held by the west African
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG, the junta has turned to the
villages near Guinea to build air fields, Ugbo said.
</P>
<P>
The arms expansion, backed by former Sierra Leonean President
Joseph S. Momo and Ukraine, is aimed at attacks agaisnt the
peacekeepers, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
But he did not say when, how and how many fighter planes have been
brought into Sierra Leone, which is under arms embargo ordered by west
African countries and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The junta seized power in a coup last May and ECOMOG has been
enforcing the embargo and economic sactions against the troubled
country.
</P>
<P>
While condemning the junta for breaching the peace accord signed in
Conakry, Guinea last October, Ugbo said, "We are still appealing the
junta to follow the peace plan."
</P>
<P>
Under the Conakry peace accord, disarmament of combatants in Sierra
Leone should begin this month and the junta will return power to
ousted president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah by april next year.
</P>
<P>
However, the junta refused to disarm the national army on the
ground that it is the legitimate armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The former rebel group, the Revolutionary United Front which allied
to the junta army, also refused to put down their weapons, saying they
are part of the national army.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Kabbah hunter militia known as Kamajors did so with the
claim that they are also legitimate civil defense group.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances, Ugbo said the plan to restore president
Kabbah by April next year has been derailed.  Eenditem

=12301624

=12301636
NNNN
00:23 00:23 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
