<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Company Failures In Britain at 7-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Business failures have fallen
to their lowest level for seven years, according to th annual
insolvency survey by Dun &AMP; Bradstreet, the financial information
company.
</P>
<P>
Total liquidations and bankruptcies dropped by almost 5000 to
36368. The number has been falling steadily since reaching a peak
of 62767 in 1992, at the height of the last recession.
</P>
<P>
This year's 11.5 per cent fall in the business failure rate is
the biggest since 1994, when the number of insolvencies declined
by 22 per cent, and the second-biggest this decade.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the quarterly rate accelerated during the year,
moving down from 10300 in the first quarter to 7980 in the final
three months.
</P>
<P>
Although every region of the UK experienced a fall in business
failures, some areas of the country saw sharper drops than others.
</P>
<P>
Philip Mellor, senior analyst at Dun &AMP; Bradstreet, attributed
the decline in business failures to the steady growth in the
British economy coupled with tougher restrictions on borrowing
imposed by banks.
</P>
<P>
Mellor said: "Provided there is no substantial downturn in the
economy, the country's annual tally of business casualties will be
back to pre-recessionary levels by the millennium." 
</P>
</TEXT>
