<HEADLINE> Kenya's Ruling Party Protests Polling Chaos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Xu Jianmei, Wang Jinyu)
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) said today it is "extremely unhappy" about
chaos amid Monday's polling, saying it offered the opposition
advantages and left thousands of KANU supporters unable to vote.
</P>
<P>
However, the party said it does not suggest another elections,
claiming its leader, incumbent President Daniel arap Moi, 73, and
in power since 1978, will surely win his final five-year term in
the country's second multi-party poll.
</P>
<P>
"We are winning," KANU National Executive Officer Geoffery
Kathurima told a crowded press conference.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of Kenyans had to cast their ballots
today after poor organization and bad weather forced an
unexpected one-day extension of the voting which was due to end
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Transport difficulties caused by bad weather, mixed ballot
papers, missing electors' names from registers, lack of ballot
papers and other technical problems caused delays, chaos and
tension nationwide in the elections.
</P>
<P>
"This was an obvious scheme by the Electoral Commission (EC)
to rig the elections in favor the opposition," said Kathurima,
charging the EC "should take full responsibility for these
irregularities".
</P>
<P>
A number of polling stations in KANU's traditional strongholds
in Rift Valley Province and parts of western and eastern
provinces failed to open until 3:00 p.m. on Monday, denying KANU
supporters' sufficient time, he said.
</P>
<P>
Two KANU supporters were killed with another two seriously
injured in the region on the day, he added.
</P>
<P>
As many as 2,000 voters in Sotik and 10,000 in Funyula
constituencies, which are power-bases of KANU, were not able to
vote "for lack of presidential ballot papers," he said.
</P>
<P>
KANU "has been targeted by elements in the Electoral
Commission in concerted with other interested parties," he
accused.
</P>
<P>
President Moi, in line with suggestions by both KANU and
opposition lawmakers, had appointed 10 more members, all
nominated by opposition parties, as electoral commissioners.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said KANU's move was responding to the similar
accusations to itself from various opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Despite common complaints, Kenyans show impressive and serious
enthusiasm for choosing leaders who they believe can be the best
to head the eastern African country into the next millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
