<HEADLINE> Protests Against Unemployment Continue in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- As 1997 is drawing to an end,
France is seeing a nationwide movement of protests against
unemployment by militant associations and trade unions, which is
exerting great pressure on the government.
</P>
<P>
A demonstration against unemployment was held today at the new
Opera Music Hall at Bastille square by union members and
anti-unemployment groups, and some 50 militants occupied the hall
of the Center of Social Action -- an official agency in charge of
social aid programs -- of the city of Paris.
</P>
<P>
The unions and militants promised to hold "strong" actions in
Paris on Wednesday, the last day of the year.
</P>
<P>
In Marseille, about 200 unemployed people blocked the tracks at
the Saint Charles railway station of the city on Monday, while
between 150 and 200 unemployed workers demonstrated in the streets
of Arras in Pas-de-Calais in northern France.
</P>
<P>
Protests were also held in a number of other cities across the
country.
</P>
<P>
The government announced today that France's unemployment rate
dropped by 0.3 percent in November to lower to 12.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
But this drop only benefits the young people under 25, while
the number of chronically unemployed people in France increased by
1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The daily Le Monde said that the under-privileged people are
taking advantage of the period of Christmas and New Year festivals
to win sympathy from the public, which pays little attention to
them in ordinary times because they have "neither status nor
means of pressure."
</P>
<P>
The daily said that the fight against unemployment shows an
essential question: Although the French economy is enriching
itself, it is incapable of eliminating poverty.
</P>
<P>
The National Secretary of the Communist Party of France, Robert
Hue, said today that the government should agree without delay to
the demand by the unemployed for a 3,000 franc (500 U.S. dollars)
bonus for Christmas and the New Year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Communist Party supports the actions of the
unemployed people, who also demand a raise of the minimum social
aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
