<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. R&AMP;D Spending Expected to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 30 (Xinhua) -- R&AMP;D spending in the United
States is expected to reach more than 216 billion U.S. dollars in
1998, a 4.66 percent growth over the 1997 level, a research
magazine predicted.
</P>
<P>
The Ohio-based Battelle-R&AMP;D Magazine put the 1997 figure as 206
billion dollars, citing the National Science Foundation estimates.
</P>
<P>
R&AMP;D spending for 1998 is expected to compose of 62.9 billion
dollars from government contributions, 143 billion dollars from
industry investments and 10.2 billion dollars from universities
and other non-profit institutions, the magazine said in its
January issue.
</P>
<P>
Major R&AMP;D investment areas include pharmaceuticals, electronics
components, scientific and mechanical measuring instruments,
non-electrical machinery, office computing and accounting machines,
and motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Government's share of R&AMP;D spending has dipped from over 50
percent before 1980 to less than 30 percent now, a trend that the
magazine expects to continue over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Under competition, U.S. companies have to pay attention to
top-line growth to meet customers' needs instead of lowering
costs, thus increasing their R&AMP;D investments, a survey has found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
