<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Establishment of China-SAfrica Diplomatic Ties Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China and South Africa will
establish diplomatic ties at the ambassadorial level starting from
January 1, 1998, Thursday, completing the normalization process of
their relations.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial to be released Wednesday, China's official
People's Daily warmly congratulates the two nations, and described
the event as having historic importance.
</P>
<P>
The editorial says the people of China and South Africa have
enjoyed traditional good relations dating back to 500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
During the apartheid times, the Chinese people showed sincere
sympathy and strong support to the South African people in their
fight against racial discrimination and persecution, it says.
</P>
<P>
In April 1994, the first multiracial elections were held in
South Africa and a new government was born. Since then, bilateral
exchanges in all fields have been active, and the understanding
and friendship between them greatly enhanced.
</P>
<P>
To normalize their ties is the common need of the two countries
to support each other politically and cooperate with one another
economically, the editorial says.
</P>
<P>
The editorial reiterates China's willingness to develop good
relations with all countries based on mutual respect for
territorial integrity and the five principles of peaceful
coexistence.
</P>
<P>
There is one China, and Taiwan is an inalienable part of
her. This is a fact that has been widely recognized by the
international community, it says.
</P>
<P>
During the apartheid times, Taiwan established the so-called
"diplomatic relations" with South Africa. It has also been trying
by all means to obstruct the normalization of ties between China
and South Africa since the birth of a new South Africa.
</P>
<P>
But the new government of South Africa ended the "diplomatic
relations" with Taiwan, and opted for full diplomatic ties with
the People's Republic of China. This has demonstrated again that
Taiwan's "pragmatic foreign policy" will not work and its act to
split the country will not get any support.
</P>
<P>
To cement and develop relations with all African countries has
been an important part of China's foreign policy. China and South
Africa have similar experiences in history, and are both
developing nations, it says.
</P>
<P>
They hold identical or similar views on many major
international issues. And there exists great potential for their
economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Following the normalization of ties, the friendly cooperation
between the two countries will surely be fully developed, the
editorial says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
