<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Slams Turkish Cypriot Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government today
slammed the Turkish Cypriot decision to suspend contacts between
the Greek and Turkish communities on the island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing here, government
spokesman Manolis Christofides described the Turkish Cypriot
decision as "unfortunate and devious," saying it "serves other
purposes and expediencies."
</P>
<P>
"The bicommunal meetings and gatherings serve the good
intentions of the Cyprus people," he said, stressing that the
Cypriot government will pursue to promote rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
"Rapprochement requires more deeds and less words. We believe
in rapprochement," he added.
</P>
<P>
Taner Etkin, foreign minister of the breakaway state in
northern Cyprus recognized only by Turkey, announced last Saturday
that all bicommunal activities are suspended, apparently in
protest of a European Union (EU) decision.
</P>
<P>
He claimed the suspension was taken to allow the Turkish
Cypriot side time to review the Luxembourg EU decision earlier
this month to include Cyprus in membership negotiations but to
exclude Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash's claim
that from now on the Cyprus peace talks would be held between "two
equal states" and not between two communities on the island, the
spokesman said "there are two communities in Cyprus, which are
recognized by the Constitution, there are no two states."
</P>
<P>
Christofides noted that the international community and a
number of U.N. resolutions on Cyprus stress there is only one
republic and one government in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Both Turkey and Denktash have recently stepped up their
efforts to achieve recognition of the breakaway "Turkish Republic
of Northern Cyprus" declared in 1983. The U.N., however, has
called on member states not to recognize it.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into a Greek Cypriot south and Turkish
Cypriot north since Ankara sent troops and took over the northern
third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia in 1974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
