<HEADLINE> Israeli Woman Posting Pig Leaflets Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Jerusalem District
Court today convicted Tatiana Susskin, who posted drawings
depicting the Muslim Prophet Muhammad as a pig, of racism,
inciting violence and supporting terror organizations.
</P>
<P>
The court is to hand down a sentence on Wednesday. Susskin, 26,
faces a jail term of up to 26 years. But defense lawyers said they
would only settle for a one-year sentence, otherwise they would
continue the legal battle to reduce it.
</P>
<P>
Susskin, from Jerusalem, was arrested in late June after
posting the pig leaflets on storefronts of 20 Arab shops in the
West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The leaflets, depicting the Prophet Muhammad as a pig writing
in the holy Koran, sparked angry Muslim protests worldwide and
Palestinian violence in Hebron and other cities.
</P>
<P>
Susskin's defense lawyers have tried to convince the court
that she was suffering from psychological illness, which they
claimed made it impossible for her to control her own actions.
</P>
<P>
But the court rejected the defense's argument after four
psychologists, who observed Susskin for a period, ruled that she
was in stable condition and fit to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
In addition to posting provocative drawings, Susskin was found
having committed other crimes against Arabs, such as throwing
stones at Palestinian cars and supporting the outlawed Jewish
extremist group the Kach Movement.
</P>
<P>
While posting the pig leaflets, she was wearing a yellow
sweater bearing the Kach's symbol of clenched fists, according to
the court.
</P>
<P>
Pronouncing the ruling today, the court said Susskin had
carefully planned and carried out cooly her action, and she was
also fully aware of the consequences of posting such offensive
leaflets against the Muslim religion.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the court after the verdict, Susskin claimed she
was a victim of the legal system that only convicts small
criminals while letting "the big fishs go free." She said she was
not regrettable about what she had done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
