<HEADLINE> Riot and Robbery Reported on New Year's Eve in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Two days from the start of 1998,
the southern French city of Toulouse experienced one night of
violence from Monday night till Tuesday while a spectacular
hold-up took place in the tourism city of Nice, according to local
media reports.
</P>
<P>
A wave of violence erupted since Monday in a working class
district of Toulouse, after one youth was killed and three others
injured in a traffic accident after they stole a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
Groups of youths charged police for causing the accident, as
the car stolen by Karim Jaoual, 20, was over-speeding and possibly
chased by police before crashing into a sign post.
</P>
<P>
Rioters threw stones at police Monday and Tuesday and burnt
vehicles, dustbins and tires in the district of Bagatelle,
inhabited mainly by immigrants and working class people.
</P>
<P>
The daily Le Figaro said that as the new year is approaching,
the number of vehicles burnt has increased in the city suburbs by
young people frustrated with their situation.
</P>
<P>
Several dozens vehicles were burnt over the past several days
in Strasbourg. More than 500 vehicles were burnt in the Alsacian
capital over the past one year.
</P>
<P>
Burning of vehicles is a way to express anger and frastrations
by young men in France, and is usually accompanied with riots in
working class and immigrant districts of big cities such as Paris
and Lyon, said experts.
</P>
<P>
A hold-up took place today in the southern tourism city of Nice
in the French Riviera. Two hooded men took away 600,000 francs
(100,000 U.S. dollars) from a currency exchange bureau, said
police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
