<HEADLINE> PLC Postponed No-confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) today decided to postpone a no-confidence vote
against the cabinet of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers continued their 25th session today in the West
Bank city of Ramallah after a one-week recess. Most PLC members
agreed to a three-month postponement on the voting of the
no-confidence motion against the cabinet, according to the
Palestinian news service JMCC (Jerusalem Media and Communication
Center).
</P>
<P>
The session was adjourned last week after some of its members
threatened to hold a vote on the no-confidence motion. They blamed
the executive authority for inefficiency and not implementing the
legislations adopted by the PLC.
</P>
<P>
To solve the conflicts between the legislators and the cabinet,
PNA President Yasser Arafat promised on Sunday to reshuffle the
cabinet in the near future, probably after his return from the
United States next month.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen ministers of the 18-member cabinet, including
Agriculture Minister Abdul Jawad Saleh, submitted their
resignations to Arafat over alleged corruption and mismanagement
of funds last August.
</P>
<P>
During today's session, the PLC also discussed a number of
resolutions, including a report of the Joint PLC-Cabinet
Committee, the Basic Law and the Civil Defense Laws. 
