<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Population Growth Continues to Perplex Poor Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Rapid population growth in
poor countries remains a global demographic problem, the U.S
Population Institute cautioned.
</P>
<P>
Despite significant fertility declines in many countries in
Latin America and Asia, the annual number of births worldwide will
be at least 132 million for many years to come, the institute
said in a report released today.
</P>
<P>
It said in its 1997 World Population Overview that this is due
the fact that most of these countries have a large population base
and a large number of women entering their reproductive years.
</P>
<P>
About 3 billion people are expected to enter their childbearing
age within the next generation and only 1.8 billion of them will
leave that period of their lives.
</P>
<P>
Today, close to 98 percent of the annual population growth
takes place in the less developed countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 percent of the world population lives in less
developed nations and 74 percent of these countries are expected
to double their populations in 30 years or less.
</P>
<P>
The report cited one of the demographic realities that about
1.3 billion people in the world live in absolute poverty on the
equivalent of one U.S. dollar or less a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Electoral Commission Denys Rigging of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Electoral Commission of
Kenya today denied accusations of the rigging of the on-going
general elections by both the ruling and opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here this evening, the commission
said that it had "carried out its responsibilities in accordance
with the provision of the Constitution without fear or favor and
without interference from any quarters."
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, Chairman of the ruling Kenya
African National Union (KANU), today accused the commission of
involvement "in a scheme to rig the on-going General Election in
favor of the Opposition".
</P>
<P>
Later this afternoon, KANU headquarters issued a statement,
saying that KANU was "extremely unhappy" with the conduct of the
commission which should take full responsibility for all
irregularities in the two polling days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Raila Odinga, leader of the opposition National
Development Party, charged today that "Moi has rigged the process
as he did in 1992, just that this time round he will not fool
anybody".
</P>
<P>
There were widespread reports of ballot paper mix-ups, missing
electors' names from registers, shortage of ballot papers and bad
weather which caused delays, chaos and tension nationwide in the
past two days.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Commission said in the statement that as a
result of severe flooding in some areas, the movement of election
materials and personnel became "extremely difficult and
hazardous".
</P>
<P>
Referring to the mix-ups, the commission explained that
British company Smith and Ouzman Ltd., supplier for the ballot
papers, failed to meet the commission's expectations in the
printing and packaging of ballot papers.
</P>
<P>
The commission's instructions on the packing of ballot papers
on the constituency basis were not strictly adhered to, thus
causing a major mix-up in the eventual distribution of ballot
papers, it added.
</P>
<P>
Commission Chairman Samuel Kivuitu today told reporters that
"at six o'clock all of them (polling stations) should be closed,"
adding that "if the time is over, it's over."
</P>
<P>
Kenya's presidential, parliamentary and civic elections began
at six a.m. Monday but had to be prolonged for 24 hours until six
p.m. today due to bad weather and poor organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
