<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: 1997 Not Positive Year for Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said today that 1997 was "not a positive year" for the
Mideast peace process and the entire region, the Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, in a year-end press briefing here today, said that
tension prevailed in the region due to lost credibility in the
peace process resulting from Israel's policies.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the deadlock of the peace drive would end, and
the concept of the peace talks, would be clear to everyone.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks are in tatters as Israel insisted
on building Jewish settlements in the occupied Arab lands and
delayed troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said this year also had witnessed tension in Iraq and in
the Gulf in addition to resurging terrorism. "In general, the year
was not at its best," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, There were positive things. he said the Arab world has
taken good stances by strengthening "cooperation in facing such
instabilities and emerging military alliances."
</P>
<P>
Moussa cited Somali reconciliation and a trend towards the
establishment of sound relations in the entire region, Iran
included, as "gains secured in 1997."
</P>
<P>
As for Egypt's foreign policy and diplomacy, the foreign
minister said great achievements were made during 1997, such as
Cairo's a clear position in the peace process and improved
Egyptian-Sudanese relations. 
</P>
