<HEADLINE> Bad Weather Forces Flight Cancellations in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of air passengers to
the northern part of Nigeria have been stranded in Lagos, the
country's economic center in the southwest, following mass
cancellation of flights due to bad weather.
</P>
<P>
The News Agency of Nigeria today quoted airport officials as
saying that the flights were cancelled because of poor visibility
caused by the haze of Harmattan, a seasonal hot, dry and
dust-laden wind originated from the Sahara.
</P>
<P>
Passengers have called on the government to provide adequate
landing equipment at the airports to facilitate air travel during
the Harmattan season, which usually goes on till the end of
January.
</P>
<P>
As of 3:00 this afternoon, no flights had taken off for the
capital Abuja in the center of the country, which normally
receives more than five domestic flights a day, said the official
news agency.
</P>
<P>
However, flights to other parts of the country like Calabar
and Port Harcourt in the east, have not been disrupted, whereas
those flying international routes arrive and depart as usual.
</P>
