<HEADLINE> Cholera Claims 188 Ugandans in Three Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Up to Monday, cholera had
claimed 188 Ugandans since it broke out three weeks ago, Health
Minister Crispus Kiyonga said here today.
</P>
<P>
The minister told a press conference here that 2,610 cases
have been reported in the whole country. Among them 1,461 have
been registered in the capital Kampala with 48 deaths.
</P>
<P>
The government is now spending 40,000 to 60,000 Uganda
Shillings (some 40 to 60 U.S. Dollars) on every cholera patient
for the treatment, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The hardest hit areas includes Kampala, Mpigi, Luwero, Mukono
and Masaka districts in the central part of the country, whereas
some areas in the eastern and western part are also affected,
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Kiyonga also spoke highly of the Uganda Red Cross for
launching a massive campaign against the killer disease since its
outbreak. A total of 100 volunteers have been involved in the
operation, the minister added. 
</P>
