<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian former president
Julius Nyerere today visited the detained Zambian former
president Kenneth Kaunda and persuaded him to end his hunger
strike, the state-owned Zambia Television Station reported.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere went to Kabwe, 150 kilometers north of the capital, to
meet Kaunda in the city's Mukobeko Maximum Prison and had a
two-hour talk with his "old" friend.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Nyerere succeeded in persuading Kaunda to
end his hunger strike, which has lasted for nearly a week since
he was arrested and detained last Thursday in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, who is alleged to have connections with the abortive
military coup last October, had said after his detention that
hunger strike is his "only" weapon to press for his freedom and
release.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, 73, also leader of Zambia's biggest opposition, the
United National Independence Party, was initially detained at
Kamwala Remand Prison in the capital and later transferred to
Kabwe, where he lives in a cell with best conditions, the state
television quoted the prison's commissioner as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, accompanied by his wife and six of his staff, arrived
in Zambia Monday to pay a three-day surprise visit to the country
amid speculations that he came to mediate an immediate release of
Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the Tanzanian former leader was entrusted
by several African leaders in the sub-region including Nelson
Mandela of South Africa and Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe with a
mission to secure Kaunda's release. 
