<HEADLINE> U.S. Motor Companies in Search of Fuel Alternatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Motor companies in the United
States are experimenting fuel alternatives for the environmental
protection purposes, industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
Ford Motor Co. has planned to produce 250,000 vehicles capable
of operating on E85 "flexible fuel" over the next four years while
Chrysler Corp. will make the E85 engine standard in 200,000
minivans each year.
</P>
<P>
All new vehicles will be capable of using the E85 blend or any
combination of E85 and unleaded gasoline, the Washington-based
research group Fuels for the Future said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
E85 is a fuel made from 85 percent ethanol and only 15 percent
conventional gasoline. Ethanol, made from corn and other sources,
is being viewed as an energy choice to drive some versions of fuel
cells, considered as a possible automotive successor to the
current internal combustion engine.
</P>
<P>
Ford intends to invest 420 million dollars to work with German
and Canadian firms to develop automotive engines using fuel cells.
</P>
<P>
The Nissan U.S. subsidiary announced on Monday that it will
introduce an electricity-powered four-passenger minivan in
January.
</P>
<P>
The vehicle uses Lithium-ion batteries as those used in
notebook computers and video recorders, the company said.
</P>
<P>
The batteries achieved the level of 90 watt-hours per kilogram,
about three times the energy density of conventional lead-acid
batteries.
</P>
<P>
The minivan model could have a maximum driving range of 120
miles, the company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
