<HEADLINE> China Grants 80 Tank-containers to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Eighty new liquid
tank-containers provided by China today went into service on the
Tanzania-Zambia Railway (TAZARA).
</P>
<P>
Kingston Mkandawire, managing director for TAZARA, expressed
satisfaction over the quality of the tank-containers at a
hand-over ceremony here in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
They will "solve quite a lot of problems" for TAZARA which has
long suffered from acute shortage of oil tanks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ma Zhihe, the Chinese Economic and Commercial Representative
who signed the contract to grant the tanks on behalf of the
Chinese government to TAZARA, said it's the first time for China
to design, produce and export such tanks with internationally
advanced technology in accordance with an agreement between the
Chinese, Tanzanian and Zambian governments in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The 1CC-type tanks in line with international standard were
manufactured by the Xi'an Locomotive Rolling Stock Factory under
the Ministry of Railways of China and certified by the China
Classification Society (CCS).
</P>
<P>
The multi-purpose tanks, used for transporting oil as well as
chemical liquids on trains, automobiles and vessels, are able to
provide door-to-door service, said Sun Kai, vice president of the
Xi'an plant.
</P>
<P>
The tanks, each with a capacity of 24.71 cubic meters, arrived
at the port in the Tanzanian capital on December 21 and have
passed technical appraisal by TAZARA.
</P>
<P>
The 1,860-km railway from Dar es Salaam, capital of Tanzania,
to Zambia's Kapiri Mposhi was built with the aid of the Chinese
government in the 1970s. It is the largest aid project China has
ever launched abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
