<HEADLINE> Drug-Related Emergency Room Visits Drop 6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Emergency rooms in the
United States witnessed a six percent drop in drug cases in 1996,
the government said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The number of cocaine, heroin and marijuana cases remained
steady from 1995 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
The decrease, small but statistically significant, is
considered attributable to decreased cases involving legal drugs.
</P>
<P>
While calling these results "another hopeful sign" of progress
in efforts against drugs, Health and Human Services Secretary
Donna Shalala said in a statement Monday, "they also signal that
our work to prevent substance abuse and treat addiction is far
from finished."
</P>
<P>
Overall, there were 487,564 drug-related emergency room visits
in 1996, down from 517,764 in 1995, according to the Drug Abuse
Warning Network's annual survey, which polls a representative
sampling of U.S. hospitals to measure health consequences of drug
abuse.
</P>
<P>
Half the cases were drug overdoses, and another 37 percent were
attempted suicide, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The most common cases involved alcohol use in combination with
another drug, followed by cocaine and heroine.
</P>
<P>
Officials said a leveling off is significant given the steep
increases in illegal drug use and emergency room visits between
1990 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Monday White House National Drug Policy Director
Barry McCaffrey said, "The slight success we are seeing encourages
us to continue our hard work." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
