<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of pro-British
Protestants attended the funeral of loyalist paramilitary leader
Billy Wright in a Northern Ireland town today, leading to a high
tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
Wright, chief of the Loyalist Volunteer Force (LVF), was killed
by republican inmates inside the top security Maze prison near
Belfast on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Wright's coffin was escorted through the Protestant town of
Portadown by an "honor guard" of 18 men, dressed in black
trousers, white shirts and black ties, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of police and soldiers were on standby in a major
security operation in Portadown where the funeral was held.
</P>
<P>
Two hours before Wright's funeral, the Catholic community in
Coalisland attended a funeral of Seamus Dillon, a former Irish
Republican Army (IRA) guerrilla who was shot dead by the LVF on
Saturday night in revenge for Wright's murder.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 mourners followed Dillon's coffin to the local
Catholic church, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Britain said on Monday it was tightening security at the Maze,
which houses 600 Protestant and republican extremists in the
biggest guerrilla prison in western Europe. 
