<HEADLINE> US Calls for Release of Kaunda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
urged Zambia's government to release former President Kenneth
Kaunda, arrested last week under emergency laws.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that he ought to be released, and we believe that
the judicial system in Zambia can run its course, that any charges
that there might be would have to be rendered publicly, and that
due process be given in this case," State Department spokesman
James Foley told a briefing.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, 73, held in a maximum security prison in central Zambia
after arrest last Thursday on charges of being involved in a coup
attempt, was said to be suffering severe physical discomfort in
prison.
</P>
<P>
The United States has called for his release. Last weekend,
Jesse Jackson, special U.S. envoy for Africa, intervened on
Kaunda's behalf and got assurances he is well and will be
prosecuted promptly.
</P>
<P>
Foley said that, given the former president's role and his
status, "he ought to be released" regardless of the seriousness of
the charges against him.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda led Zambia to independence in 1964 and was called
"father of the nation." Now he leads the opposition United
National Independence party after being defeated by current
President Frederick Chiluba at presidential elections in 1991.
