<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China-S. Africa Diplomatic Ties A Milestone: Qian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen today hailed the establishment of
diplomatic ties between China and South Africa as an important
milestone in the history of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Qian and South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo signed a
joint communique in Pretoria today on the forging of diplomatic
ties at ambassadorial level between the two countries as from
January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of diplomatic ties marks the beginning of a
new chapter of friendly relations and cooperation between the two
countries, Qian told a reception held here in his honor.
</P>
<P>
The reception was hosted by Wang Xuexian, director of Chinese
Center for South African Studies and the expected first Chinese
ambassador to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Qian said exchanges between the Chinese and South African
peoples can be traced back to last century.
</P>
<P>
"After the founding of new China in 1949, the Chinese
government and people consistently sympathized with and firmly
supported the people of south Africa in their struggles for
racial equality and national liberation," Qian told an audience
of several hundred people at Sandton Sun Hotel.
</P>
<P>
He said China, in particular, stood firmly by South Africans
"in their just struggles against apartheid under the leadership
of the ANC (African National Congress)."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people joined the South African people in
celebrating the birth of new South Africa and rejoiced at their
achievements in nation-building in many areas in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, each with its own strength in economic
development and natural resources, share a high degree of
complementarity, said Qian.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese foreign minister, two-way trade has
risen sharply in the past few years, from 14 million U.S. Dollars
in 1991 to 1.34 billion Dollars in 1996, and to an expected 1.6
billion Dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Qian also mentioned South Africa's economic, trade, financial
and civil aviation links with Hong Kong, over which China resumed
the exercise of sovereignty last July.
</P>
<P>
Qian said a bilateral trade agreement and an investment
protection agreement, which are under preparation, will put in
place a new framework for the future trade and economic
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"We have every reason to believe that after the normalization
(of relations), China and South Africa are destined to become
economic and trade partners of ever increasing importance," Qian
said.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral cooperation on the diplomatic front, Qian said
China and South Africa, both developing countries that have
considerable influence in Asia and Africa respectively, could
work together on many issues.
</P>
<P>
"We have common language on many important international
issues. With our diplomatic relations established, we will step
up our consultation and cooperation in international affairs,
play a greater role in global and regional affairs and join hands
in safeguarding the rights and interests of developing countries
and promoting the cause of peace and development for mankind."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government attaches importance to developing
friendly relations and cooperation with South Africa, said Qian.
</P>
<P>
"In keeping with the principles of enhancing understanding,
increasing trust, expanding cooperation and achieving common
development, we are ready to work with our South African friends
to actively explore and open up new areas and new ways of
bilateral cooperation so as to further enrich the friendship
between the two countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diplomatic Ties with China Long Overdue: S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo said today that his country would have
established diplomatic ties with China long ago if it had not
been for the evil system of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
"Had it not been for the apartheid system, the establishment
of diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of China would
have been a foregone conclusion a long time ago," Nzo told a
reception in honor of visiting Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen.
</P>
<P>
Nzo and Qian signed a joint communique earlier today in
Pretoria on the establishment of diplomatic relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a cordial speech at the reception hosted by Wang Xuexian,
the Chinese ambassador-in-waiting, Nzo said the normalization of
relations accommodated to the international trend and was a
"natural outcome".
</P>
<P>
"It would have been totally untenable that a situation should
continue to exist where one of the leading countries in Africa
does not have formal relations with one of the leading countries
in Asia and the world," he told an audience of several hundred
people.
</P>
<P>
"The continuation of such a situation would have been
inconsistent with decisions taken by international bodies such as
the U.N. and the OAU (Organization of African Unity), international
law and the state practice followed by the overwhelming majority
of countries," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"This would also have been a denial of the major role that
African countries have played to secure the rightful place of the
People's Republic of China at the United Nations in 1971."
</P>
<P>
Nzo said the two countries will enter "a new era" with the
establishment of diplomatic relations, adding, "This will be an
auspicious occasion for both countries."
</P>
<P>
The forging of diplomatic ties between the two countries is
the natural outcome of a long evolutionary process of contact
between them, dating back more than three centuries, according to
the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
"In many ways, the strong bonds between China and Africa have
been forged through similar historical experiences. Both have
suffered dearly at the hands of colonial powers, including
humiliations and injustices because of discrimination," Nzo
added.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the founding of the People's Republic of
China in 1949, China unselfishly became a steadfast moral and
material supporter for Africa's struggle for liberation and
democracy, Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that during those long and bitter years of struggle
against apartheid, much encouragement and inspiration was drawn
from the examples by the great Chinese leaders such as Sun
Yat-sen, Mao Zedong, Zhou Enlai and Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
"It (China) today provides once again an example for Africa --
this time for the economic liberation and renaissance of Africa.
</P>
<P>
"We in South Africa in particular and Africa in general have
been following with great admiration how China, in adapting free
market principles to China's own unique situation, has
transformed its economy and society in less than 20 years,
resulting in the greatest reduction in poverty ever recorded in
human history.
</P>
<P>
"Through these transformations, the People's Republic of China
has achieved a status and position in the world where it enjoys
the respect and attention of everyone.
</P>
<P>
"The South African government is grateful that notwithstanding
China's newly elevated status in the international political
system, it has not forgotten the developing world, especially
Africa. We look forward to China joining other leading powers in
the world in assisting in the development of Africa," Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
South African and China, both developing countries, share many
similar ideals and objectives. Both countries are for example
committed to the principle that in the international political
and economic system, the "strong should not dominate the weak"
and that the interests of developing countries should be
adequately safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, South Africa, as a non-aligned country
pursuing an independent foreign policy, is looking forward to
forging a strategic partnership with China for the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
He believed that the establishment of diplomatic relations
will give impetus to the existing ties.
</P>
<P>
"Let us in partnership, with enthusiasm, seize the
opportunities that this new relationship will bring about to the
mutual benefit of both countries," he wished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
