<HEADLINE> FM: Iran Disappointed to Egypt's Stance on Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Iran today expressed
disappointment to Egypt's attitude towards Iran, saying that at
present there were no grounds for normalizing the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The recent statements of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak were
disappointing and only repetition of Egypt's past positions, said
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi in an interview with the
official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA).
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi contended that the Egyptian president was not aware of
the realities in the Islamic Republic of Iran, and did not show a
necessary political will.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak reportedly said recently in a televised interview that
he wanted to be sure of Iran's intention before any normalization
in Cairo-Tehran relations.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt was cautious in resuming diplomatic relations
with Iran, and that "we must first feel that the issues of
exporting the (Islamic) revolution, offering shelter to terrorists
and naming streets in Iran after them are over."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was referring to Iran's alleged support for Egyptian
terrorist groups, and Tehran's Khaled Eslamboli Street named after
the assassin of late Egyptian president Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Minister said that it was a regret that
Egypt was repeating its past positions and attributing the
internal problems to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of understanding and cooperation of
the Muslim world, saying that Egypt needed more time to take
serious strides towards improving relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the remarks of both Mubarak and
Kharrazi implicated a setback of the relations between Iran and
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
During the eighth summit of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference held here on December 9-11, Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa and Kharrazi expressed the readiness of their countries
to improve the strained ties.
</P>
<P>
Iran severed its diplomatic ties with Egypt after it granted
political asylum in 1979 to Iran's late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi
toppled in the Islamic Revolution of Iran in the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
