<HEADLINE> Britain Unlikely to Share Falklands with Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said here today that there was no question of sharing
Falklands (Malvinas) sovereignty with Argentina without the
agreement of the local residents.
</P>
<P>
Argentine President Carlos Menem, due to visit London early
next year, reportedly said in Buenos Aires recently that he would
discuss the issue of Argentina's claim over the islands and would
suggest sharing sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps we could talk about shared sovereignty, which would be
a significant step," Menem told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the BBC Radio early today, Cook
ruled out the possibility of sharing Falklands (Malvinas) with
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
"We have always made it perfectly clear that the wishes of the
Falkland (Malvinas) islanders are what counts. They do now want
shared sovereignty and in those circumstances there is no question
of us agreeing shared sovereignty," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
On Menem's visit to Britain, Cook noted that Menem would
exchange views with British government leaders on various issues
on bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"President Menem's visit will not be about the Falklands
(Malvinas) Islands. It was established between the two countries
that President Menem's visit was about the very strong bilateral
relations between Britain and the new democratic Argentina," Cook
said.
</P>
<P>
Menem will be first Argentine President to visit Britain since
the Falklands (Malvinas) War in 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
