<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1430 GMT December 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON-- The United States received 13,000 more first-time
claims for unemployment benefits during the Christmas week than
the week before, the Labor Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment benefit applications totaled 318,000 last
week, up from 305,000 the week before.
</P>
<P>
Despite the increase, the unemployment rate in November stood
at 4.6 percent, still the lowest in 24 years.
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl Wednesday expressed
confidence in his country's economic outlook in 1998, but
cautioned that Germany still needs more reforms in order to adapt
to dramatic changes in the world.
</P>
<P>
In a year-end interview with the German business daily
Handelsblatt, Kohl said that current economic data are pointing to
a German economic growth of 2.5 percent in 1997 and a growth rate
of up to three percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia's total foreign trade volume increased by two
percent in 1997 to 136 billion U.S dollars, Russian Minister of
Economic Relations and Trade said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Mikhail Fradkov said Russia's export
decreased while import increased in 1997. But the country still
enjoyed a favorable trade balance of 3.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- A military officer was found stabbed to death in a
forest in Paris Wednesday, while a 50-year-old woman was found to
have had her throat cut in her home, according to local media
reports.
</P>
<P>
Gerald Capliez, 44, a lieutenant in the French army, was found
to be killed with several stabbings on his back and head in the
Bois de Boulogne Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- A man's suicide attempt in the Paris subway on
Wednesday morning stalled operation of a subway line for a time,
reported Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
The man jumped into the track when a train was approaching the
platform on the 13th line of the subway, which lies in the city's
southern part. The train had to be lifted to disentangle the man.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Two people have reportedly claimed seeing a Fiat
coming out of the tunnel of Alma in Paris on August 31, seconds
after the crash which killed Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
The two anonymous people -- one man and one woman -- said the
white Fiat Uno was driven by a European man of some 40 years old
with brown hair, said the daily Aujourd'hui/Parisien Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
