<HEADLINE> Mozambican Soldiers Replace Striking Garbage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The City Council of Maputo has
decided to mobilize soldiers to transport the garbage in the
city, where the garbage workers started strike on December 24,
local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Maputo City Council (CMCM) spokesman David Simango said
here Tuesday that drivers from the army took the place of the
garbage clearance service bureau workers Tuesday to transport the
garbage from the city.
</P>
<P>
The garbage workers have been ordered to be suspended until
further notice for "not cooperating with the city council in
garbage clearing," Simango said.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the garbage cleaners, who started their
"silent strike", have left piles of garbage uncleared since the
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
Artur Canana, the city mayor, promised to give the city a
thorough face-lift by getting the garbage quickly cleared.
</P>
<P>
Poor sanitation is believed to have caused the spread of
malaria, which has claimed over 250 lives.  
</P>
