<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report on Major Events in HKSAR Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A special report explaining
the key issues which have dominated the first six months of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region was released here on
Wednesday for distribution overseas.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said the 22-page report has been sent to
all 10 Hong Kong Economic and Trade Offices in the United States,
Europe and the Asia-Pacific region in response to tremendous
international interest in Hong Kong since it became a SAR of China
on July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The report includes an overview of the major events in the past
six months, as well as sections on the economy and economic
prospects, infrastructure development, politics, the rule of law,
human rights, education, tourism, the People's Liberation Army
Garrison and the avian flu.
</P>
<P>
It says that Hong Kong's return to China has gone smoothly and
its people are running their own affairs, as promised in the Basic
Law, stressing that Hong Kong's successful transition has clearly
proved wrong those critics who predicted a doomsday scenario after
July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report mentioned the commitment that President Jiang Zemin,
premier Li Peng and other Chinese government leaders have
underlined on many occasions to the "one country, two systems"
policy.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Asian economic crisis, the report says that Hong
Kong will still be able to forge ahead with important road, rail
and port projects as well as new initiatives in education and
tourism promotion.
</P>
<P>
It also reinforces the HKSAR government's determination to
maintain the Hong Kong dollar link to the U.S. dollar and explains
why the exchange mechanism is needed.
</P>
<P>
It is inevitable that Hong Kong will be affected by the
regional financial crisis and that GDP growth in 1998 will slow as
a result, the report says.
</P>
<P>
However, the report states: "balancing this are a number of
factors that will help Hong Kong to cope with the current downturn
better than most of our competitors and will help us recover more
quickly once favorable conditions return."
</P>
<P>
These factors include: lower inflation rates than neighboring
economies; the high capital adequacy ratios and prudent lending
policies of Hong Kong banks; the upside to the downturn in the
property market through lower rents and prices, thus increasing
competitiveness and keeping inflation in check; currency stability
through the link with the U.S. dollar, the report says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
