<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Foreign Trade Shows Strong Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
economic powerhouse, has racked up 22.2 billion U.S. dollars in
foreign trade at the end of November.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the municipal Foreign Trade and Economic
Commission said the city expects to finish more than 14.5 billion
U.S. dollars of exports this year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total export volume, industrial products will account
for 93 percent. Electrical machinery products have become more
popular, with the export value jumping from 17.9 percent of
industrial exports in 1993 to present 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
Major destinations for the city's exports are Southeast Asia,
Oceania countries, Latin America, Middle East and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Xiaoming, head of the trade commission, said that China is
confronting an increasing product cost and funds shortage, a
continuing challenge for the country's export sector.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has formed a group of foreign trade conglomerates in
an effort to improve the operating scale. It has also introduced
share-holding and mergers to make the city's 725 foreign trade
enterprises more competitive on the international market.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 218 of Shanghai's overseas foreign trade companies
have formed six regional conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Shanghai has placed equal emphasis on cargo
trade, technological trade and service trade. The city's
transaction of technology is expected to top 650 million
U.S. dollars, 3.5 times that of 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Pudong New Area in Shanghai has conducted one-fifth of the
city's exports, with its value registering 2.8 billion
U.S. dollars for the first 11 months of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
