<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak President-Elect to Be Sworn In Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Rafiq Tarar, who won an
absolute majority of votes in Wednesday's presidential election,
will be sworn in as Pakistan's ninth president Thursday morning,
official sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Tarar, candidate from the ruling Pakistan Muslim League (N) for
the presidential poll, secured a total of 374 votes out of the 457
calculated votes in the presidential elections held simultaneously
in the national and four provincial assemblies, Chief Election
Commissioner Qadeer Chaudhry announced here late Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Shahban Mirani, former defense minister and nominee of the
major opposition Pakistan People's Party (PPP) obtained a mere 58
votes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Muhammad Khan Sherani from Jamiat-e-Ulema Islami
(JUI) won 22 votes, Raja Saeeduz Zaman (independent) got one and
the PML(N)'s covering candidate Haleem Siddiqui polled two votes.
</P>
<P>
The remaining two candidates did not secure any vote in the
poll.
</P>
<P>
The president-elect will be sworn in on Thursday morning in the
Presidential House. The oath-taking ceremony will be administered
by Chief Justice of Pakistan's Supreme Court Ajmal Mian.
</P>
<P>
The total electoral college votes are 476, including 87 from
the Senate, 217 from the National Assembly and 43 each from the
four provincial assemblies.
</P>
<P>
According to the Election Law, whosoever secures 51 percent of
all the 476 electoral college votes, or 239 votes, will be
declared next president of this South Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
However, it is still uncertain whether Tarar will hold the
office he won on Wednesday. Tarar was allowed by the Lahore High
Court on December 19 to participate in the election after his
earlier disqualification of candidature by the Election
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Former acting chief election commissioner Mukhtar Ahmad
Junejo's order to disqualify Tarar's candidature for his alleged
remarks against judiciary remains suspended.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
