<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Kills 38 in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhang Dacheng, Gu Ming)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The devastating floods
in Tanzania have left 38 people dead and tens of thousands of
others homeless, Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye told a press
conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The floods, starting from early December, have paralyzed the
central railway and a number of roads and bridges in the country,
said Sumaye, who was represented by Jacob Tesha, the Press
Secretary to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Areas along the central railway were worst hit by the floods.
In Kilosa District alone, more than 104,000 people have been
rendered homeless.
</P>
<P>
The floods have also damaged eight bridges on the railway
between Kilosa and Mzaganza districts.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the government has decided to provide
an additional fund of 500 million Shillings (about 800,000 US
Dollars) for the emergency repairs of the damaged facilities.
</P>
<P>
A sum of 313 million Shillings have been released so far by
the Ministry of Works for the rehabilitation, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the whole rehabilitation work will take six
months, but key structures are expected to come back to normal in
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The floods, brought about by the El Nino weather phenomenon,
have also threatened the output of maize, cotton and other crops,
but the prime minister said coffee farmers may be spared.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, most of the roads leading to
wildlife parks in the north have also been cut off, which may
hurt tourism in the country.
</P>
<P>
As the rains continue to pour down, fears of the outbreak of
cholera, typhoid and other diseases have increased. The
government has admonished people to observe hygiene, such as
boiling drinking water and using toilets.
</P>
<P>
Economic losses are yet to be known, as the floods have
blocked traffic and cut off telecommunications to several areas,
thus making statistics impossible.
</P>
<P>
As meteorologists have forecast that the above average
seasonal rains will continue until next April, the World Food
Program has expressed the fear that Tanzania's food shortage
resulting from last season's drought may worsen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
