<HEADLINE> PSA Condemns Use of Zambian Air Controllers in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Public Service
Association (PSA) President Givemore Masongorere today condemned
the move by the government to engage Zambian air traffic
controllers to replace those fired recently.
</P>
<P>
The PSA urged the government to develop a culture of dialogue
with its workers whenever there is a problem.
</P>
<P>
"The PSA is naturally very disturbed by the move to fire local
air traffic controllers replacing them with foreigners," he said,
adding "We condemn the move in the strongest sense."
</P>
<P>
The government last Wednesday fired 67 air traffic controllers
who went on strike demanding better working conditions and
salaries.
</P>
<P>
Masongorere said bringing in people from Zambia would create
bad blood between the workers in the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) region.
</P>
<P>
"The PSA would like to come in and mediate, and try to bring
the two parties to an amicable understanding. We would rather
solve the problems internally than bring in a neighbor," he said.
</P>
