<HEADLINE> Malaysians Urged to Make Sacrifice to Revitalize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad urged all Malaysians to make sacrifices to help
steer the country towards economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The people would have to endure all sorts of pressures and make
sacrifices, he said in his New Year message broadcast over radio
and television Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
He said that one sacrifice for them was to save and invest
confidently despite knowing that their savings would depreciate if
the value of the ringgit continued to fall.
</P>
<P>
"If we have no confidence in our own currency and because of
that we don't save or invest and instead convert our money to
foreign currencies or deposit them overseas, this will still cause
our currency to depreciate all the same," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Preserving the value of the ringgit is a crucial and common
responsibility of all Malaysians because others would not bother
to, he said, adding that the decline in the ringgit's purchasing
power for domestic goods and services would not be the same as its
depreciation by more than 30 percent against the U.S. dollar since
last July.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir reiterated that Malaysia would not borrow from
international institutions as that was not the approach to resolve
the current problems.
</P>
<P>
He said that in taking on the present economic challenges, the
people should not easily give up and admit defeat. Instead,
Malaysians should show willingness to face hardships and make
sacrifices to defend the country's independence and integrity.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said "our struggles not only have yet to end but they
are only getting more crucial."
</P>
<P>
He thanked all Malaysians for their expressed confidence in the
government and in himself, saying their pledge of support should
be translated into action to help the country recover
economically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
