<HEADLINE> Sono Likely To Coach South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Former national soccer
star Jomo Sono looks set to succeed Clive Barker to coach South
Africa's national soccer team.
</P>
<P>
Barker resigned on December 20 after the African champions and
World Cup qualifiers' dismal performance at the Confederations Cup
in Saudi Arabia, where they finished bottom of Group B behind
Uruguay, the Czech Republic and the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
Sono, 42, owns and coaches Jomo Cosmos, the Premier League's
underdog whose greatest achievement was reaching the 1993 African
Cup-Winners Cup semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Another local contender for the 10,000-dollars-a-month post is
Gordon Igesund, who coached Manning Rangers from the port city of
Durban to first place in the 1997-1998 national championship.
</P>
<P>
Dutch pair Jo Bonfrere and Clemens Westerhof, Frenchman
Philippe Troussier, Englishman Terry Venables and Russian Victor
Bondarenko are also short listed for the job.
</P>
<P>
After Barker's resignation, national association officials
hinted at a foreign replacement with high-profile Venables or
former Nigerian coach Bonfrere.
</P>
<P>
This triggered an outcry from local coaches who claimed foreign
coach would destroy the natural style of South Africans and they
were interested only in money.
</P>
<P>
Since South Africa's returning to international football in
1992, locals Tshabalala and Barker and Peruvian Augusto Palacios
have coached the national team.
</P>
<P>
The vacant post of South African soccer coach will be filled on
Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
