<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Upbeat About Germany's Economic Outlook In 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 31 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
Wednesday expressed confidence in his country's economic outlook
in 1998, but cautioned that Germany still needs more reforms in
order to adapt to dramatic changes in the world.
</P>
<P>
In a year-end interview with the German business daily
Handelsblatt, Kohl said that current economic data are pointing to
a German economic growth of 2.5 percent in 1997 and a growth rate
of up to three percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
There are also signs of a gradual improvement next year on the
country's sluggish job market where unemployment is hovering at
about 4.3 million, or over 11 percent, in 1997, Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in his New Year's speech televised on Wednesday,
Kohl also said that Germany would have to make hard choices about
its future development next year when the general election is due
to be held in September.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, who has already announced to seek an unprecedented fifth
term in office since 1982, will face serious challenge from the
main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD), which is at
loggerheads with Kohl's centre-right ruling coalition on most of
Germany's domestic issues, including a major tax reform.
</P>
<P>
"The coming year will see heated debates about what is the
right course the country should take in the future," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
In order to be competitive in a dramatically changing world,
Germany must continue its course of renewal and push through
necessary reforms, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also called on his countrymen to maintain what he
said are the world-recognized German values of inventiveness,
conscientiousness and diligence, adding that these values are the
best preconditions for more investment and more jobs in Germany.
</P>
</TEXT>
