<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Direct Election of Deputies Draws Crowd of Candidates (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The number of deputies to the
county people's congress is about 3,000 in central China's
municipality of Wuhan. But the number of candidates nominated by
voters, parties and organizations for the election exceeds 16,000.
</P>
<P>
In some electoral districts, a candidate was jointly nominated
by more than 1,000 voters. The number of candidates in some
districts was finally decided after four or five screenings.
</P>
<P>
The election in Wuhan epitomizes those at different levels
across the country.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute such an unprecedented democratic atmosphere
in the election of deputies to the people's congress to the direct
election of village and township deputies in China during the last
few years.
</P>
<P>
The direct election system of village and township deputies is
maturing in China, said Qiao Xiaoyang, deputy-director of the
Commission of Legislative Affairs under the National People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
The law stipulates that direct election of deputies to the
people's congress should be held at the village and township
levels since the 1950s. Direct election was expanded to the county
level in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
This will be the sixth county-level direct election, and the
first since the new election law was promulgated in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The election began six months ago in the country's 2,800
counties involving nearly 800 million voters.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 counties will complete the election today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Direct Election of Deputies Draws Crowd of Candidates (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some 90 percent of the candidates in east China's Zhejiang
Province were elected through joint nomination of more than 10
voters.
</P>
<P>
"It is a remarkable characteristic of the deputy election this
time that a high ratio of candidates are jointly nominated by more
than 10 voters," said Zhao Yongqian, chairman of the Xiaoshan City
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that it is a breakthrough in China's election system
and it guarantees that voters can choose the people they trust to
be deputies to the people's congress, "so that they can speak and
do things on behalf of the people."
</P>
<P>
"Another symbol for the maturing of direct elections is the
introduction of competition and multi-candidate elections," said
Qiao, adding that it guarantees the election will fully mirror the
will of voters.
</P>
<P>
Lu Qinghua, a 30-year-old farmer, is a newly elected deputy to
the Langxi County people's congress in east China's Anhui
Province. Lu, a candidate jointly nominated by voters, is one of
the district's two elected deputies.
</P>
<P>
With the economic and cultural growth and the improvement of
people's democratic and legislative awareness, the people's
enthusiasm to participate in public affairs has risen greatly.
Statistics show that more than 90 percent of the voters in a large
number of places have participated actively in the deputy election.
</P>
<P>
"Direct election has expanded the democratic basis of the
people's congress above the city level," Qiao said, adding that
the combination of direct and indirect elections is an important
characteristic of China's current system.
</P>
<P>
"Direct election is the base and, to a certain degree, the
democracy of indirect elections depends on the degree of direct
election," Qiao added.
</P>
<P>
He said the expansion of direct elections to the county level
will provide experience and create conditions for the expansion of
direct elections to a wider range in the future.
</P>
<P>
"China's election system will be improved step by step, and the
county will implement an entirely popular, equal, direct and
secret voting system when conditions mature," Qiao said, quoting
Liu Shaoqi, the late president of the country. However, he did not
specify when and to what level China will expand direct election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy-Conservation Law to Take Effect Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Energy Conservation Law of
the People's Republic of China will go into effect tomorrow. The law
is considered by experts as an important step for the nation to
better manage and properly use energy.
</P>
<P>
As a country with a large population and relatively limited
energy resources, China's economic development long has been
restricted, an official with the State Economic and Trade
Commission said today.
</P>
<P>
However, he continued, waste has remained a big problem though
the country suffers from a serious energy shortage, "so there is
great potential to exploit energy-savings."
</P>
<P>
He said that if only one percent of consumed energy is saved, the
country could save more than 10 billion yuan (1.3 billion
U.S. dollars) of industrial costs yearly, as well as reducing
pollutants released into the natural environment.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Conservation Law was passed in November by the 28th
session of the Standing Committee of the Eighth National People's
Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
