<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Economy Grows by 7.6 Percent in 1997: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore economy grew
by 7.6 percent in 1997, better than earlier expected, while the
country will have a more difficult year in 1998, Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong said in his New Year message on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that 1997 was a most eventful year,
with the most important development being the on-going regional
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Predicting 1998 to be a more difficult year, he said, "Slower
growth in our neighbors will affect Singapore. Trade with the
region will fall. Banks will see less financial activities, and
make fewer loans to the region. Fewer ASEAN (Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) tourists will visit Singapore."
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister pointed out that Singapore's
economic fundamentals are sound and the country has large foreign
reserves, runs substantial budget surpluses, and has no foreign
debt. Besides, Singapore has political stability, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the current gloom, the medium and long term prospects
of the region are promising," Goh said.
</P>
<P>
Provided the countries in the region undertake necessary but
painful adjustments, robust growth should resume after two to
three years, he said.
</P>
<P>
Goh also stressed that Singapore must use the next few years to
consolidate and sharpen its competitive edge by upgrading skills
and developing talent. The country will also continue to "add
value" to the economies in the region and help them overcome their
difficulties and grow.
</P>
<P>
"Then we can ride the next wave and surge ahead when the region
picks up again," the prime minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
