<HEADLINE> Tarar Elected Pakistani President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The official candidate of
the ruling Pakistan Muslim League (N), Rafiq Tarar, was elected
president of the country on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 68-year-old Tarar, a former judge of the Supreme Court, is
to become the ninth president of Pakistan since its independence
in 1947.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest results released by the Election
Commission, Tarar won 381 votes in the presidential elections held
simultaneously in the National and four Provincial Assemblies.
</P>
<P>
Shahban Mirani, former defense minister and nominee of the
major opposition Pakistan People's Party (PPP), got 77 votes.
</P>
<P>
Counting of votes in the Provincial Assemblies of Baluchistan
and Punjab is still under way.
</P>
<P>
The total electoral college votes are 476, including 87 from
the Senate, 217 from the National Assembly and 43 each from the
four Provincial Assemblies.
</P>
<P>
According to the Election Law, whoever secures 51 percent of
all the 476 electoral college votes, or 239 votes, will be
declared the next president of this south Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
However, it is still uncertain whether Tarar will hold the
office he won on Wednesday. Tarar was allowed by the Lahore High
Court on December 19 to participate in the election after his
earlier disqualification of candidature by the Election
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Former acting chief election commissioner Mukhtar Ahmad
Junejo's order to disqualify Tarar's candidature for his alleged
remarks against judiciary remains suspended.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
