<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Electrician Turns Face Musical (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese electrician has been
playing Carmen, Jingle Bells and many other musical pieces by
thumping his head with his fingers.
</P>
<P>
His unusual musical performance will be broadcast live by CCTV,
China's most prominent television station, at the end of January
when Chinese are observing their most important holiday, Spring
Festival.
</P>
<P>
For Cui Wenping, an electrician from the Foreign Language
Publishing and Distribution Administration (FLPDA), this
performance will be his 50th in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
It's not just his head that can be musical. At times he taps
his forehead, the bridge of his nose and his teeth for different
sounds.
</P>
<P>
The trick to producing music is to form a resonant box in his
head by holding his throat, tongue and mouth in the right position
and then beating at the muscle for sounds.
</P>
<P>
His "musical instrument" has a 2 1/2-octave range. With a
microphone, the range can be broader, he said.
</P>
<P>
"To develop face music into an art that can be something so
funny as to be talked about by people at their meals, I need to
work harder, (just as Lenin once said) `study, study and study',"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The 43-year-old man said that he taps his head every week.
"Otherwise the muscles turn clumsy and I can't play the notes
right," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cui said that he invented his musical style accidentally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Maldives Continues to Be Tourist Paradise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Come and enjoy a few days of
stay in a place where abundant sunshine, crystal-clear lagoons,
fine white beach and peace are absolutely natural.
</P>
<P>
That's what the Maldivians want you to do in their country. The
image of a tourist paradise has been projected by the Indian Ocean
nation for 25 years in the world tourism market.
</P>
<P>
The Maldives has the most beautiful tropical scenery, graceful
coconut palms leaning over warm sea water, coral reefs promising
great snorkeling and scuba diving, and more.
</P>
<P>
With the increasing pace of life in the modern world, it has
become the ultimate getaway for those who like doing nothing but
enjoying noise- and-pollution-free nature.
</P>
<P>
During the 1980s, tourism became one of the most important and
highest growing sectors of the Maldivian economy.
</P>
<P>
The industry has brought in 70 percent of the country's foreign
exchange, 40 percent of government revenue and almost 20 percent
of the Gross Domestic Products (GDP) in 1997, the year that
commemorated 25 years of tourism in the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
The country designated 1997 as "Visit Maldives Year," targeting
350,000 visitors. Though it's a bold target, compared with 280,000
tourist arrivals the previous year, the country achieved it at the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Maldivian Tourism Minister Ibrahim Hussain Zaki, brimming over
with optimism about the future of the industry, attributed the
success first to political stability. There has been no political
turmoil or ethnic war as in its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, pragmatic tourism policies ensure the Maldives to be
a superb tourist destination in the world. In pursuing quantity of
visitors, the country doesn't sacrifice quality.
</P>
<P>
"What we want is quality tourism. If we want quantity, we can
easily have it," said the minister, who paid a visit to Sri Lanka
recently.
</P>
<P>
Only 74 of the more than 1,000 uninhabited islands have been
developed into resorts.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the industry enjoys a very successful partnership
between the public and private sectors in developing the industry.
Tourism officials are often invited to speak in various regional
or international forums.
</P>
<P>
A properly stipulated price strategy also benefits the industry
to a certain extent.
</P>
<P>
The Maldivians have made sure that backpackers with budget of
10 to 15 U.S. dollars a day cannot get in. At the high end of the
tourism market, what the Maldives offers can cost at much as 700
dollars a day. Even at the low end, prices don't dip below 50
dollars.
</P>
<P>
As the industry grows, so does the sentiment in the Maldives
that tourism, and the economic prosperity that comes along with
it, cannot exist unless the pristine purity of the country's
environment is well-preserved.
</P>
<P>
"Our tourist product is primarily dependent on the natural
environment, so there must be the right balance between tourism
and environment. We cannot develop one at the cost of the other,"
Zaki explained.
</P>
<P>
With annual tourist arrivals exceeding the Maldivian population
of 260,000, the future prospects for the industry turn out to be
rosy.
</P>
<P>
Islands further away from the capital atoll are now being
developed. Under a tight regulatory framework intended to protect
environment, 14 islands have been offered for new resort
development projects in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Nine islands will be developed by Maldivian investors, some of
whom will collaborate with foreign partners. The remaining five
islands will be tendered in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Apart from a fleet of sea planes and helicopters that have been
in service, hovercraft and hydrofoil will be brought in to enable
quick transportation between the Male International Airport and
each of the resorts.
</P>
<P>
Now the government is making plans to let more Maldivians get
into the sector in the new year. The local youth are getting
necessary training both on the job and in the Hotel School, which
is being expanded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Election Free, Fair Despite Chaos: Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A senior electoral official
today said Kenya's general elections taking place on December 29
and 30 were free and fair although there were confusions and
chaos.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Kivuitu, Chairman of the Electoral Commission, told a
press briefing that "Kenyans excelled in the numbers that turned
up to cast their votes and the remarkable state of peace that
prevailed all round."
</P>
<P>
He paid tribute to Kenyan voters, political leaders and the
churches, saying that "it was indeed a superb display of maturity
and patriotism".
</P>
<P>
The electoral official noted that polling was closed at six
o'clock p.m. on December 30 all over the country and counting of
votes is now in progress.
</P>
<P>
Voter turnout so far has ranged from about 65 percent to 89
percent, according to the electoral official.
</P>
<P>
There were widespread reports of ballot paper mix-ups, missing
electors' names from registers, shortage of ballot papers and bad
weather which caused delays, chaos and tension nationwide in the
two polling days.
</P>
<P>
Because of the chaos, the presidential, parliamentary and
civic elections were extended for a further 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
Kivuitu repeated his complaint that a British firm which
printed the ballot papers should bear some responsibility, adding
that people should "put blames partly to the printer and partly
to the commission".
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, National
Chairman of the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU),
accused the commission of its involvement "in a scheme to rig the
on-going general elections in favor of the Opposition".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Social Democratic Party presidential candidate, Charity
Ngilu, was quoted as saying that her party would not accept the
results of the election as serious anomalies had marred the poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
