<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post-handover Hong Kong Sports Striving with Validity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Similar to all the sectors
of its social life, Hong Kong's historic handover to China and
establishment of the Special Administrative Region (SAR) on July 1
this year ushered in a new era in local sports.
</P>
<P>
Worries by some for post-handover local sports' status built up
when it was proposed to send a large Hong Kong SAR delegation to
the Eighth National Games in October in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
But, international sports leaders including Juan Antonio
Samaranch, President of the International Olympic Committee (IOC),
had even before the handover confirmed that Hong Kong, after its
handover to China, would keep its internationally recognized
independent status as before.
</P>
<P>
Two days after the handover, Samaranch reached agreement in
Hong Kong with Arnaldo de O. Sales, President of the local Amateur
Sports Federation and Olympic Committee (ASF&AMP;OC), on HKSAR's
participation in such future international competitions as the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The five-point document ensures that local athletes continue to
compete independently in future international competitions such as
Olympic Games and local Olympic Committee keeps its status
recognized by the IOC.
</P>
<P>
It also rules that the local Olympic Committee be renamed as
"The Amateur Sports Federation and Olympic Committee of Hong Kong,
China" and has its emblem to be redesigned.
</P>
<P>
The instructive document wiped away worries and settled down
arguments around the HKSAR's status in international sports arena.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Joao Havelange, President of the
International Football Federation (FIFA), had ensured Hong Kong
sports' autonomy after the handover. And in early December,
FIFA's executive committee issued a statement, which reaffirmed
that the Hong Kong Football Association would keep as before its
FIFA membership and compete in future international competitions
as an independent body.
</P>
<P>
The National Games in Shanghai brought about new chances and
challenges as well to Hong Kong's sports. A 168-athlete
delegation, the first ever since Hong Kong became a SAR of China,
was warmly welcomed at the Games' opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"At that very moment, I really felt the pride of being a
Chinese and the tenderness of being a member of the big family,"
recalled a member of the HKSAR delegation.
</P>
<P>
The victory by Hong Kong's ace cyclist Wong Kam Po in the men's
180-kilometer road race, which brought Hong Kong's first ever
National Games gold medal, became the biggest news in Hong Kong
sports since last summer when Lee Lai Shan, the most famed product
of local sports machine as an ace woman wind surfer, won for Hong
Kong its first ever Olympic medal -- a gold at last year's Atlanta
Games.
</P>
<P>
And, with the victory which upset China's top racer Tang
Xuezhong, Wong was later named one of Best Athletes of the Games
and, before the New Year's Eve, was listed as one of the country's
Top Ten Athletes of the Year.
</P>
<P>
Although Wong's victory was Hong Kong SAR athletes' only
medal-winning performance in Shanghai, the number one harvest for
the delegation was the experience of competing in the country's
top-class sports gala. Leading officials of many Hong Kong sports
associations took the chance to discuss with their mainland
counterparts on such topics as ways to further the cooperation
between them and to promote Hong Kong sports.
</P>
<P>
The local sports has very positive prospects since it enjoys
the advantage of its geographical location adjacent to China's
mainland, which provides excellent chances for exchanges and
mutual support.
</P>
<P>
SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa has on many occasions
expressed his optimism on the prosperity of HKSAR's sports. "Both
Hong Kong and Hong Kong sports will enter a new era when Hong Kong
reunifies with the motherland," he said in January.
</P>
<P>
He guaranteed that the future HKSAR government would inject
enough funds into programs promoting local sports. "Don't worry
about money," he ensured.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong sports would have much better chance and advantage
in the future after Hong Kong's reunification with China. I'm
optimistic of this," said John Hung, Chairman of the Hong Kong
Sports Development Board (HKSDB).
</P>
<P>
"China is one of the world's sports powers. HKSAR's sports
shall take the orientation of promoting exchanges and mutual
supports with the mainland so as to have both programs steamed
up," said Timothy Fok, Vice-Chairman of the HKSDB.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong SAR has remained, since the handover, one of the
world's most important economic, financial, tourist and
information centers. And, it is still vigorous in promoting
sports with ambitious programs for local development and projects
for hosting international competitions.
</P>
<P>
Bright prospects are ahead as SAR strives with might and
validity to attain a higher standard both for its athletes and its
residents' health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
