<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Electrician Makes Face Musical (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the spring of 1980, after playing his harmonica all morning,
he tapped his strained face for relief. The sounds surprised and
intrigued him.
</P>
<P>
For several days he tapped his face until it was black and
blue, his gums were swollen and his knuckles ached. He was unable
to play a simple tune, but persevered.
</P>
<P>
Cui first tapped his face with one finger, then used three
while drawing inspiration from the Chinese three-string instrument
called the "Sanxian'er." He learned to use five fingers after
studying another Chinese musical instrument, the "Pipa."
</P>
<P>
His skills are so good now that he can tap music off his head
just as easily as he waves his leg. But even playing the most
solemn music, he has to "box" his ears to make loud notes.
</P>
<P>
Cui, who has been an electrician for 27 years, also plays the
violin, clarinet and other instruments. His musical repertoire
also includes plucking a comb and rubber belt.
</P>
<P>
He often finds contradiction between his job as an electrician
and a musical performer. But his boss helps him by granting eaves
whenever he needs to perform. Sometimes Cui flies out of Beijing
after work and returns early the next morning so that he can
perform his job.
</P>
<P>
Cui also wins unrelenting support from his wife, a shop
assistant, and his daughter, a high school student. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
