<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Loses $8b Yearly to Foreign Shippers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria loses an estimated
eight billion U.S. Dollars annually to foreign shippers for the
import and export of its oil and non-oil products, an industrial
leader has disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Due to non-participation of indigenous shipping companies, the
country loses about two billion dollars annually to foreign
shippers in the lifting of crude oil, according to Alhaji Buba
Galadima, Director-General of National Maritime Authority (NMA).
</P>
<P>
Another six billion dollars is lost to foreign shipping
interests in dry cargo shipment, project cargo, containers,
general cargo imports and exports, he said at NMA's 10th
anniversary celebrations held in the capital Abuja Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nigeria sells its crude oil on Free on Board
(FOB) basis and is the only member of the organization of
petroleum exporting countries which does not freight its crude
oil and own its tankers.
</P>
<P>
"Our foreign terms of trade which have our exports to be
conducted on FOB and the import on CIF (cost, insurance and
freight) basis make it extremely difficult to effectively partake
in cargo carriage," Galadima said, quoted by press reports today.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the story is not any different in the
gas sector.
</P>
<P>
Galadima explained that efforts "to reverse these unfavorable
trends, which had seen us taking strong position at higher
levels, continue to be challenged and thwarted by the foreign
shipping interests".
</P>
<P>
"To date, it has remained difficult, for instance, to open
foreign offices abroad to monitor shipments," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nigerian ships are still being detained in
foreign ports on the slightest excuse, while service charges due
to NMA are denied, delayed or under-declared by foreign shipping
interests.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the government to come to the aid of NMA for it
to surmount some of the problems.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Minister of Transportation major-general
Ibrahim Gumel said the government is presently looking into the
details of how indigenous shipping companies can participate in
the carriage of crude oil, liquified natural gas and other
freight exports and imports.
</P>
<P>
According to industry sources, Nigerian shipping companies
have over the years sought to participate in the lifting of the
country's crude oil.
</P>
<P>
To demonstrate their capability, six indigenous carriers
formed a consortium two years ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
