<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tarar Wins Pakistani Presidential Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Senator Rafiq Tarar, the
official candidate of the ruling Pakistan Muslim League (PML-N)
and its allied parties, won the presidential election Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
While counting is still under way in the three of the four
provincial assemblies, the 68-year-old Tarar, a former judge of
the Supreme Court, has secured 312 votes including 243 from the
National Assembly and 69 from the Sindh provincial Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Tarar swept the House by obtaining 243 votes of the total 298
votes polled at the National Assembly, according to the results by
the Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
According to the Election Law, whoever secures 51 percent of
all the 476 electoral college votes, or 239 votes, will be
declared the next president of this south Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
Shahban Mirani, former defense minister and the nominee of the
major opposition Pakistan People's Party (PPP), secured 39 votes
while Muhammad Kan Sherani from the Jamiat-e-UlemaIslami (JUI) won
seven votes.
</P>
<P>
Seven votes at the National Assembly were declared invalid,
while six Parliamentarians failed to cast their votes.
</P>
<P>
Results coming from the Provincial Assembly of Sindh show that
Tarar secured 69 votes as against 34 won by Mirani. Out of a
total of 109 votes in the Sindh Provincial Assembly, 105 votes
were cast.
</P>
<P>
However, it is still uncertain whether Tarar can hold the
office he has won. Tarar was allowed by the Lahore High Court on
December 19 to participate in the election after his earlier
disqualification of candidature by the Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
Former acting chief election commissioner Mukhtar Ahmad
Junejo's order to disqualify Tarar's candidature for his alleged
remarks against the judiciary remains suspended.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
