<HEADLINE> Shanghai Regulations to Govern Chain Store Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- New regulations governing
chain store operations in Shanghai, China's largest commercial
center, will go into effect on January 1, 1998, according to
sources from the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
The new regional regulations will govern the city's chain store
sector which consists of over 2,600 sales outlets with total sales
of over 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion U.S. dollars) through the end
of November. Specific articles in the regulations clarify the
definition of a chain store, mode of operations and registration
formalities.
</P>
<P>
The regulations stipulate that only entities with headquarters
facilities, a unified distribution system and more than 10 sales
outlets can be registered as a chain store companies.
</P>
<P>
A supermarket must cover an operating space of over 500
sq.m. and use bar codes on more than 90 percent of its products,
excluding fresh meat products, according to the regulations.
</P>
<P>
A convenience store must have floor space of over 50 sq.m. and
provide services for more than 16 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
Experts fully expect the regulation to be highly conducive to
promoting more orderly competition in Shanghai's chain store
sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
