<HEADLINE> Renewed Communal Clash Kills 6 in West Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Six people were killed and burnt
beyond recognition when fresh clash broke out between rival Ife and
Modakeke communities early this week in west Nigeria's Osun State.
</P>
<P>
The killing, denied by community leaders, has been confirmed by
State Commissioner of police Sunday Aghedo, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Another three people were reportedly kidnapped during the fresh
onslaught, which came barely two weeks after leaders of the feuding
communities signed a peace pact at the instance of the State
Administrator Anthony Obi.
</P>
<P>
The renewed violence is at least the fourth round in a series since
the first unrest was triggered off by the relocation of the Ife-East
local government headquarters from Modakeke to Oke-Ogbo in Ile-Ife
last August.
</P>
<P>
The bloody clashes have claimed lives of some 100 people,
injured 200 more others and caused huge economic loses as many
houses were burnt and other properties damaged.  
