<HEADLINE> Low Inflation Rate, Best Gift to Poor: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram said here Wednesday that containing inflation at 4
percent is the best gift offered by the United Front government to
the poor in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The year of 1997 was a roller-coaster year for the country's
economy due to political uncertainty. The Reserve Bank of India
has forecast a six percent economic growth for this fiscal year
(April 1, 1997--March 31, 1998) against a 6.8 percent last year.
This was not a very happy conclusion, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he did not buy the argument that a four percent or
less inflation rate was anti-growth.
</P>
<P>
Slowdown in exports was attributable to the economic slowdown
on a global scale as well as devaluation of Asian currencies. Poor
performance of industrial and export sectors would not last long
because the country's economic fundamentals were strong, he added.
</P>
<P>
</P>
