<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Inflation Rate Falls to 8.8% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has brought down to the
single digit mark its inflation rate, which dropped to 8.8
percent in November from the previous month's 10.1 percent, the
Federal Office of Statistics (FOS) says.
</P>
<P>
The achievement falls within the 15-percent budget target for
the year.
</P>
<P>
"The average annual rate of rise of consumer retail prices for
the 12-month period ending November 1997 was 8.8 percent," FOS
reported, quoted by The Vanguard today.
</P>
<P>
But FOS warned that it was not yet a relief for consumers as
"the level of prices are still very high when compared to the
corresponding level at the base period."
</P>
<P>
According to the government agency, the consuming price index
(all items) of 2,837.5 naira for November 1997 was 28.375 times
that of September 1985 in terms of average prices of goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
The FOS report said the single digit inflation rate only
indicated "a substantial slow-down in the upward movement of
consumer retail prices."
</P>
<P>
Average retail prices of consumer goods and services "are
still experiencing price increase," it added.
</P>
<P>
FOS attributed the rapid drop of the inflation rate to the
government's tight fiscal and monetary policy stance.
</P>
<P>
The combination of policy measures, however, also helped in
starving the economy of funds, resulting in the weak purchasing
power of the public and a build up of inventory in the
manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
The agency also warned that low inflation rate was not a good
yardstick for an economy that is not growing or performing well.
</P>
<P>
"One digit inflation does not mean that the economy is totally
good. Inflation can be brought down when people are too poor to
buy," FOS said.
</P>
<P>
It is learned the Nigerian government is to adopt a reflation
policy to promote economic growth in the new year.
</P>
<P>
According to National Planning Minister Chief Ayo Ogunlade,
the thrust of the 1998 budget would include consolidating gains,
revitalizing the economy and an easier import of goods by
manufacturers and attractive atmosphere for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The government will also increase the salaries of public
servants.
</P>
<P>
These policy measures, when implemented, are expected to
increase the purchasing power of both individuals and
enterprises, leading to an upward movement of prices, analysts
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
