<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- For the first time in history, the movement by the jobless
in France is forcing the authorities to respond. According to
official statistics published Tuesday, France now has 3,114,600
jobless people. A dozen of them protested at offices of government
agencies in charge of employment and social aid, while the
regional headquarters of the Socialist Party in Bordeaux was
besieged on Tuesday, as protesters wanted to remind the prime
minister of his promise to tackle the problem of unemployment with
results.
</P>
<P>
-- At least 350 people were killed in Algeria in less than 10
days, which did not take into account the casualties of security
force and isolated cases of attacks and killings. Faced with this
atrocities which the press attributed to Islamists who saw in the
month of fasting a "period proper for jihad (holy war)," the media
have been diffusing for days "an appeal for vigilance" by the
Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- For the first time since September 1996, the unemployment
rate of France dropped to less than 12.5 percent in November. But
protests by unemployed people are continuing in the field with the
support of some political parties and unions such as the Communist
Party and the Confederation Generale du Travail. Even Jean-Pierre
Raffarin, a leader of the opposition Union for French Democracy,
has expressed support to the protesters, describing their action
as "an outcry against exclusion."
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac will address the nation on
Wednesday evening to express his New Year good wish. At the end of
a year marked by the failure of dissolution of parliament and
election of a leftist majority, the chief of state is expected to
stress what unites the French people rather than what divides
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
