<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't Announces Merger of Four State Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Wednesday announced a plan to merge a number of state owned banks
into one to improve the health of the country's banking sector and
provide foreign banks of international reputation with the
opportunity to become shareholding partners.
</P>
<P>
"The preparation process of the merger will be carried out from
January-March 1998 while the actual merger is expected to be
completed not later than July 31, 1998," Finance Minister Mar'ie
Muhammad said here after meeting with President Soeharto at his
residence.
</P>
<P>
As part of the economic reform measures, the merger and
restructure of government banks is meant to accelerate the
revitalization efforts of state-owned banks, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie said the government will also form a credit settlement
company -- with the status of state-owned company -- tasked to
solve or liquidate all non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
The four state-owned banks that will be merged into one are
BAPINDO (Bank Pembangunan Indonesia), Bank Bumi Daya, Bank Dagang
Negara and Bank Ekspor Impor Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Following the merger, non-performing loans will be removed from
the banks involved and transfer them to the newly created credit
settlement company to ensure there is improvement in the quality
of assets resulting from the four merged banks, Mar'ie said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government's decision to allow foreign banks
to become shareholders will ensure that the merged banks would
become a strong financial institution that can compete globally.
</P>
<P>
On why the government is giving opportunity to foreign banks to
become shareholders, he said, "we want to improve our skills and
credibility and transfer the technology."
</P>
<P>
The government's decision to merge the four state-owned banks
is the second step to make them more efficient.
</P>
<P>
On November 1 this year, the government closed 16 insolvent
private banks in a bid to make the banking sector more healthy.
</P>
<P>
Economists and monetary institutes here regards the existing
240 commercial banks in Indonesia as far too many for the
country's banking sector at this stage of economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
