<HEADLINE> Tarar Wins Pak Presidential Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Senator Rafiq Tarar,
official candidate of the ruling Pakistan Muslim League (PML-N)
and its allied parties, won the presidential election Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 68-year-old Tarar, a former judge of the Supreme Court,
swept the House by obtaining 243 votes out of the total 298 votes
at the National Assembly, according to the results by the Election
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Shahban Mirani, former defense minister and the nominee of the
major opposition Pakistan People's Party won only seven votes out
of a total 298 votes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Muhammad Khan Sherani from the Jamiat-e-Ulema Islami
(JUI) secured seven votes.
</P>
<P>
Seven votes at the National Assembly were declared invalid
while six Parliamentarians failed to cast their votes.
</P>
<P>
According to the Election Law, whosoever secures 51 percent of
all the 476 electoral college votes, or 239 votes, will be
declared next president of this South Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
However, it is still uncertain whether Tarar will hold the
office he wins. Tarar was allowed by the Lahore High Court on
December 19 to participate in the election after his earlier
disqualification of candidature by the Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
The order by former acting chief election commissioner Mukhtar
Ahmad Junejo to disqualify Tarar's candidature for his alleged
remarks against judiciary remains suspended.  
</P>
</TEXT>
