<HEADLINE> China Imports 48 Passenger Aircraft in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- China has imported 48
passenger aircraft in 1997, including 20 aircraft from Boeing, 19
from Airbus and six from McDonnel Douglas, in order to meet the
demands of the thriving domestic market.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) obtained 46
aircraft through outright purchases or leases.
</P>
<P>
The remaining two aircraft, the first business aircraft in the
country, were imported by the Yuanda Group, a non-state company in
Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
China, a major market for international aircraft manufacturers,
ordered 97 passenger planes this year, including 50 from Boeing
and 30 from Airbus. This year's purchase volume was the
largest-ever for China's civil aviation sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
