<HEADLINE> Vietnamese PM Calls for Poverty Alleviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Prime Minister Phan
Van Khai, in his year-end interview with Vietnam News Agency
(VNA), assigned priority to poverty alleviation efforts.
</P>
<P>
The country now has some 14 million people, or one out of every
five Vietnamese, living in poverty, Khai said.
</P>
<P>
Calling for priority settlement for poverty and other problems
in the rural area, the prime minister said people there account
for 80 percent of Vietnam's total population.
</P>
<P>
There should be policies that create momentum for agricultural
and rural development oriented toward industrialization,
modernization and cooperation, Khai said.
</P>
<P>
For such an end, he said, there are also needs to strengthen
the administration and party organizations, and to promote
democracy at the grass-roots level.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister told the VNA that economic integration into
the region and the world is necessary for Vietnam's development.
</P>
<P>
"Vietnam will maintain national independence, sovereignty and
interest in the integration process, pushing industrialization and
modernization while adhering to socialist principles."
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that Vietnam's economy continues to grow at a high
rate after nearly two years of implementation of the resolution
adopted by the eighth party congress. 
</P>
