<HEADLINE> Ugandan Farmers Advised to Plant More Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan farmers were advised
to plant more rice to cope with the worst rainy weather since
1907, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Current El Nino will not end until nine months later, warned
Anthony S. Okkelo, the director of crop resources under the
Agricultural Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Local traditional crops such as millet and maize did not fit
to the prolonged rains, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged drought by October and torrential rains since
late November had hindered the growth and delayed collection of
coffee seeds and cotton, the main cash crops of Ugandan farmers.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics of Ugandan authorities, coffee
export in September and October this year dropped from last
year's 792,839 bags to 310,433 bags.
</P>
<P>
Coffee export earns 65 percent of foreign exchange for
Ugandans. Each bag of coffee contains 60 kilogram of its seeds.
</P>
<P>
Cotton, another main export crop, also was predicted to
decrease to 60,000 185-kilograms bales this year from last year's
110,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
