<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Applying Computers to Farming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- An illiterate ethnic Chinese
farmer cannot tell what a computer is, yet he believes in the
"stuff" since he has tasted its sweet.
</P>
<P>
Jiasan Daha, a veteran farmer of the Yi Nationality in Ninglang
County, of southwest China's Yunnan Province, turned to computers
for advice this summer when he found his apple trees suffering
insect diseases. And in a matter of a few seconds, the computer
did tell him what to do.
</P>
<P>
He is only one of the numerous Chinese farmers who have
benefited from a nationwide project called Computerized Agronomist
System, which stores varied agro-sciences, farming knowledge and
agriculture-related information.
</P>
<P>
The computer gives specific answers and solutions to any
questions and problems raised by farmers, based on scientific
calculation.
</P>
<P>
The project, initiated by the State Science and Technology
Commission, has been extended to nearly 100 counties across the
country, covering more than 26 million ha of farmland.
</P>
<P>
"Is is encouraging that such high-techs have been spread so
quickly in outlying poor areas," said Gao Zhenning, vice-chairman
of the China Association for Science and Technology, after an
on-the-spot inspection in the county.
</P>
<P>
Not only farmers but also county leaders did not know anything
about computers years ago. Local people used to turn to "slash and
burn" method for farming.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning, Jiasan Daha would never believe that the
"stuff" would know how to do farming. But he was convinced when
his neighbors collected higher grain output with computers'
help. And he is now a regular visitor to the local computerized
agronomist system center.
</P>
<P>
"High-techs have really been turned into a productive force
in our county," said Li Xingshun, the county's Party secretary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
