<HEADLINE> IDB: Assistance for Latin America Rises to New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) said Tuesday its financial help for Latin
America and the Caribbean reached a record high in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Disbursements exceeded 5.5 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, up 1.2
billion dollars against 1996, said IDB President Enrique Iglesias
in his year-end address to the Board of Executive Directors.
</P>
<P>
Approved loans totaled 6.0 billion dollars for a record 99
lending operations, including 327 million dollars complemented by
564 million dollars in syndicated loans for private infrastructure
projects without government guarantees, an IDB record for private
sector lending.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Washington-based IDB financed 294
technological cooperation projects on a nonreimbursable basis for
a total of 73.6 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Lending for social programs, mainly for health and education,
constituted 43 percent of the IDB lending in Latin America and the
Caribbean in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In promoting regional integration, the IDB provided a line of
credit to the Central American Bank for Economic Integration as
well as financing for transportation corridors that link Uruguay
with other Mercosur countries and the Bolivia-Brazil natural gas
pipeline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
