<HEADLINE> US Urged to Revise Policies toward Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official has
said that Washington should revise its policies toward Iran and
correct the "misconceptions" of the American people about Iran,
local daily Iran News reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Iran News published today, Iranian Deputy
Foreign Minister for legal and international affairs Mohammad
Javad Zarif said the United States had to acknowledge that Iran is
an active country and could not be isolated.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has to have a realistic approach toward the
new international climate, the end of the Cold War, the change in
the international structure, as well as recognizing the Islamic
Republic of Iran as a pluralistic system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zarif said that the eight Islamic summit held here on December
9-11 proved that allegations and propaganda against Iran were
"unfounded, because all regional countries have unanimously
announced that the source of their anxiety is Israel."
</P>
<P>
He said that all the ambiguities should be resolved and
allegations retracted, adding that "we will adopt a more active
policy in this regard."
</P>
<P>
Zarif also denied the report about the visit of a U.S. Senator
to Iran, saying that "I am not in charge of Iran-U.S. relations,
but I strongly deny this rumor."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi
Monday also denied a visit of U.S. Congressman Tom Lantos to
Iran, saying that "we have no information about such a plan."
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi also dismissed the report that Iranian Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi called for better ties with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
After Iranian President Mohammad Khatami announced his
willingness to have a dialogue with the American people, there
were many reports and rumors about possible rapprochement between
the two rival countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Mohammadi said that there was no new developments
between the two countries and many Iranian officials urged
Washington to revise its policies toward Iran as a goodwill
gesture to Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the United States broke diplomatic relations in 1980
after the Iranian Islamic revolution and the U.S. Hostage
crisis and the Untied States has been imposing economic sanctions
against Iran ever since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
