<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chinese Audiences Enjoy Opera and Ballet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese audiences had ample
opportunities to enjoy opera and ballet during 1997 -- the
"International Opera and Ballet Year" initiated by the Ministry of
Culture on January 5.
</P>
<P>
Sun Xiaohong, an official from the ministry, said 17 art
troupes from eight countries, including China Japan, Russia,
Israel, and Austria, took part in the event. The troupes staged 30
outstanding operas and ballets for a total of 350 nights in over
20 major cities throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
More than 430,000 Chinese people have journeyed to local
theaters to watch world-famous opera and ballet classics
such as "Le Nozze di Figaro" performed by the Vienna State Opera,
"Turanto" by the National Opera of China, "Swan Lake" by the State
Ballet Troupe of Russia, and "Red Detachment of Women" by the
National Ballet Troupe of China (NBTC).
</P>
<P>
Chinese audiences have gained considerable knowledge and
understanding of opera and ballet and, at the same time, have
learned to enjoy high-quality performances of traditional European
art forms dating back over 400 years.
</P>
<P>
"I'm delighted to have had the opportunity to enjoy ballets
performed by the world's top dancers," said Zhao Weifeng, a lawyer
in Beijing. Zhao noted he was fond of watching the movie version
of the modern Chinese ballet "White-haired Girl" during his
boyhood.
</P>
<P>
NBTC Director Zhao Ruheng said that the troupe has presented 59
performances of five ballet classics during 1997, including "Swan
Lake," "Sleeping Beauty," and "Don Quixote." Thousands of Chinese
residents fell in love with the art, a combination of charming
dancers, beautiful stage design, moving stories, pleasing music,
and skillful performances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chinese Audiences Enjoy Opera and Ballet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The NBTC also invited a dozen excellent ballet experts and
artists from Great Britain, Denmark, France, and Russia to join in
art exchange programs, and developed a series of cooperative
performances with young Chinese dancers, said Zhao, adding that
"the activities were a sign of further links between Chinese and
western arts."
</P>
<P>
Zi Huajun, a leading researcher on the art of dance, said that
modern Chinese opera and dance started early this century with the
development of western opera and ballet in China.
</P>
<P>
"Regardless of the place of their origin, outstanding arts are
treasures for people throughout the world, and the only way for
art forms in a country to improve is to engage in exchanges and
learn from arts in other countries and regions," said Zi. For
example, active art exchanges between central areas in China and
foreign regions yielded a prosperous era of dance and music
culture during the Han Dynasty (206-220 B.C.) and the Tang
Dynasty (618-907).
</P>
<P>
This year's cultural exchange programs and art performances
helped Chinese art troupes learn more about European ballet and
opera, establish a profitable culture market in China, and serve
the desire of Chinese audiences for high-quality art programs,
according to Zi.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Culture has extended great effort to introduce
outstanding foreign art genres to Chinese people. Apart from the
year of international opera and ballet, the ministry also
sponsored the International Symphony Year in 1996, and will
sponsor the International Fine Arts Year in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
