<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks Aim at Higher Loan Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The increasingly risk-aware
Chinese banks are taking active measures to improve their loan
efficiency, while gradually reducing the existing bad loans.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the banks have focused on improving their
loan-extending systems, strengthening internal control, and
stepping up the risk prevention effort during the past year as
required by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
All the major Chinese commercial banks have endorsed the
ambitious goal to cut down their existing bad loans by two to
three percentage points a year for the coming three to five years.
</P>
<P>
Inefficient and bad loans are labeled as a major pain for the
Chinese banking sector. The central bank estimated the nation's
bad loans at more than one trillion yuan, about 20 percent of the
total loans.
</P>
<P>
The major blame may be dated back to the traditional planned
economic system, under which the banks paid more attention to the
quality of their services rather than the loan efficiency and loan
risks. Over-speculation in the real estate sector and the
financial difficulties of the state-owned enterprises also
resulted in an increase in inefficient bank loans.
</P>
<P>
However, the liquidity, safety and efficiency of the bank loans
gradually rose to become the top concern of the Chinese banks from
1995, when the central government decided to commercialize the
once state-owned specialized banks.
</P>
<P>
And the banks' efforts to fight bad loans and improve loan
efficiency have paid off this year, said a central bank official,
pointing to the fact that all the Chinese banks have set up a
scientific loan-extending system, improved the internal
supervision mechanism, and stepped up the administration of their
loan assets.
</P>
<P>
As an immediate outcome, the four largest state commercial
banks have reported smaller growth but increased quality in
outstanding loans, with the loan structure further improved and
some bad loans either recalled or written off.
</P>
<P>
The shift of the Chinese banks' focus to improving loan
efficiency and increasing risk awareness showed that the sector
was a substantial step closer toward the final goal of becoming
commercialized, said Jin Guanwen, a loan management official with
the Agricultural Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
However, the "digestion" of bad bank loans is complicated and
demands the efforts from the whole society, and is closely related
to the maturing of the market economy and the continuous reform of
the state enterprises, according to Wang Guogang, deputy director
of the Financial Research Center under the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"But we may count on a gradual decline in the bad loans in the
coming years, as a result of the gradual progress in the economic
performance of the enterprises," added Wang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 08:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Developing Laser System to Counter Katyusha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Israel will be able to deploy
an anti-missile laser system capable of shooting down Katyusha
rockets fired from Lebanon in early 1999, local newspaper Daily
Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted an Israeli report as saying that field
tests of the Nautilus laser, being jointly developed by Israel and
the United States at a cost of 160 million U.S. dollars, would be
conducted at the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
Nautilus is a tactical high energy laser, whose main function
will be to protect against the short-range Katyusha rockets fired
into Israel by Lebanese resistance guerrillas in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The idea involves a high energy beam being directed at an
incoming warhead and capable of destroying it, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
It said that the U.S. had hoped that a prototype of the
Nautilus would be ready for installation in northern Israel at the
end of this year, but the project reportedly has been delayed due
to funding and technical problems.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985 when Israeli troops occupied Lebanon's
1,200-square-kilometer area in the south with the claimed aim of
protecting its residents in the northern area, Lebanese
guerrillas often use Katyusha rockets in attacking Israeli
occupation forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> County Economy Becomes Dynamic Sector (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 31 (Xinhua) -- Jinxiang County in East
China's Shandong Province, one of the nation's major grain and
cotton bases, was still a poor area only five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Things have changed, however, and the mid-sized county has been
growing by an average annual rate of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Jinxiang, with a population of 600,000, is one of China's over
2,000 counties, including more than 400 county-level
cities. Jinxiang's high economic growth rate reflects the dynamism
of China's overall county economy.
</P>
<P>
State Statistical Bureau figures for 1997 show that the growth
rate for the county economy was between 3-4 percentage points
higher than the rate for the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Counties, with land areas ranging from 1,000 sq.m. to 3,000
sq.m. and populations of between 200,000-1,000,000 people, are the
most stable level in China's administrative structure. Counties
are, in fact, home to over 80 percent of China's population and
over 90 percent of the nation's land and mineral reserves, as well
as water, agricultural, forestry, pastoral and fisheries resources.
</P>
<P>
According to Professor Gao Huanxi, who has studied the county
economy for many years, "The development momentum for the county
economy remains strong, despite the fact that Chinese leaders
still face difficulties in solving problems with state-owned and
large urban enterprises. The county economy have emerged as one of
the most dynamic sectors in the country's overall economic
framework."
</P>
<P>
China's county economy not only includes the family,
cooperative township economies, but also state-owned industrial
and commercial businesses. The total economic volume for the
county economy accounts for over 60 percent of the total national
economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> County Economy Becomes Dynamic Sector (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Du Changwen, a local official in Jinxiang, said: "The rapid
development of our economy has benefited from a strategy of
agricultural industrialization which has further rationalized our
industrial structure and enabled industries to upgrade."
</P>
<P>
Like Du, local leaders in many of China's counties have
achieved success in organizing economic development with a view
towards industrialization. They have managed to achieve industrial
advantages by promoting market-oriented agricultural and
by-product processing.
</P>
<P>
Industrialization has also promoted the rapid development of
the secondary and tertiary industries in rural areas, with said
industries becoming energetic growth points in the county
economy. For example, two large enterprise groups and 76 private
enterprises in Jinxiang County are engaged in processing "white
garlic", a well-known local product. Jinxiang's export volume for
garlic currently accounts for 70 percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Agriculture, the over 20,000
agricultural and by-product processing enterprises China has
established in recent years are predominantly distributed in
counties and represent a new force driving development of the
county economy.
</P>
<P>
"China's reforms have been most effective in counties. The
reforms have enabled flexible township enterprises to develop
rapidly, and many medium and small county-owned enterprises to
find various means for opening and expansion," according to
Professor Gao.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 100,000 small- to medium-sized state-owned
enterprises at the county level. Since the 15th National Congress
of the Communist Party of China, various localities have
accelerated their pace for restructuring and reshaping said
enterprises. They have also adopted various economic patterns such
as share-holding, leasing, auctions and joint stock ownership to
strengthen the major force in the county economy.
</P>
<P>
The most important result of county reform in recent years
centers on the fact that township enterprises have largely
improved their quality. Projections from the Ministry of
Agriculture indicate that national township enterprises will
achieve a 1997 added-value of 180 million yuan, up 18 percent on
1996. Their profits and taxes will also grow by over 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Professor Gao noted that the rapid and healthy development of
the county economy has not only consolidated the fundamental level
of the national economy, but has also significantly improved
infrastructure in most areas of the country without increasing
government inputs.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that China will have over 200 million surplus
rural laborers by the end of the century, with the national annual
floating population expected to hover between 60-80
million. Officials from the State Commission for Restructuring the
Economy noted that further development of the county economy will
provide more employment opportunities and beneficial conditions
for China's poverty relief campaign.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, South Pacific Nations Forge Closer Ties (2) --by Liu Dongkai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During a meeting with Australian Prime Minister John Howard in
Beijing in March, Chinese President Jiang Zemin said the two
nations should proceed from a point of strategic height in
considering the expansion of bilateral relations. Jiang added that
the two countries should proceed from the standpoint of
maintaining and promoting peace, stability and prosperity in the
Asia-Pacific Region and should fully consider both the future and
the current general situation.
</P>
<P>
In its foreign affairs and trade white paper issued in August,
the Australian government stated that it planned to forge closer
links with Asian countries such as China and Indonesia in order to
safeguard its national security and economic interests.
</P>
<P>
This year marked the 25th anniversary of the establishment of
diplomatic relations between China and the two largest nations in
the South Pacific. CPPCC Vice-Chairman Li Ruihuan attended
commemoration ceremonies in Australia and New Zealand during
visits to the two countries in December. Australian Foreign
Minister Downer also visited Beijing to attend a series of
celebrations held during the same month.
</P>
<P>
Hu Jintao, member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the CPC Central Committee and member of the committee's
Secretariat, attended a ceremony marking the 100th birth
anniversary of the late Rewi Alley, a well-known social activist
from New Zealand and an old friend of Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Trade and economic cooperation represents one of the most
notable aspects of relations between China and South Pacific
nations. China is Australia's fifth largest trade partner, and
seventh largest for New Zealand. Two of China's largest overseas
investment projects are in Australia and New Zealand, including a
joint-venture iron ore mine in Australia and a logging operation
in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
China has signed bilateral trade agreements with seven island
nations in the South Pacific, and has also signed civil aviation
agreements with a number of the nations. The agreements provide a
solid foundation for the further development of economic and trade
cooperation between China and these nations.
</P>
<P>
People-to-people contacts represent yet another outstanding
feature of Sino-South Pacific relations. The Chinese Government
has designated Australia and New Zealand as two of five official
tourist destinations for Chinese citizens. According to
projections by Australian immigration authorities, the number of
Chinese citizens traveling to Australia will double over the next
three years to reach 130,000 by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Local governments from China and South Pacific nations have
also increased contacts, with Chinese and Australian cities
establishing 31 sister-city relationships. In addition, cities in
China and New Zealand have established 13 similar relationships,
with one sister-harbor relationship between ports in the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
China actively supports efforts by the South Pacific Forum to
protect the environment, promote economic development and maintain
stability in the region. The South Pacific Forum has also decided
to establish an economic and trade representative office in China.
</P>
<P>
Local experts expressed the belief that China will continue to
work for closer ties with South Pacific nations on the basis of
the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
