<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Prices on China Market Likely to Edge Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Wheat prices on the Chinese
market are thought likely to edge up in 1998 due to an
expected fall in output and falling prices this year, today's
China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
As most wheat producers in China have suffered severe drought
since last October, the per-unit wheat production in 1998 will be
lower than that in 1997. Consequently, the total output will be
less than last year's record high, 122.6 million tons.
</P>
<P>
As domestically produced wheat cannot meet market demands, China
is expected to import more wheat in 1998 than in 1997, but much
less than in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
As wheat stores are sufficient in early 1998, the wheat supply
will roughly equal the demand.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the State Statistics Bureau on
Monday, grain output in 1997 is expected to be 492.5 million tons,
a record high in two years running. Experts had predicted
that China's grain reserves would hit a record high in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, influenced by low wheat prices in 1997 and producers'
and consumers' expectations, wheat price rises in 1998 will not be
too radical, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Wheat prices on the Chinese market have been dipping in 1997,
mainly stemming from good wheat harvests over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of 1997, wheat output, at 22.25
million tons, hit a record high and led to an oversupply. Prices
on the international market also kept going down, which posed a
great threat to the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the domestic prices have dropped to their lowest
level for three years. Statistics indicate wholesale prices
declined continuously from 1,744 yuan (210 US dollars) per ton in
March to 1,410 yuan (170 US dollars) in August.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women, Children Enjoying Better Health Care in Guangxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to loans from the World
Bank, women and children in south China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region are now enjoying much better health care.
</P>
<P>
With 8.82 million US dollars of loans from the World Bank and
76.73 million yuan (9.2 million US dollars) of supportive funds
from local governments, maternity and child care projects have
been carried out in the region's 30 relatively impoverished
counties.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the death rate of pregnant and lying-in
women in the counties on the average has been reduced from 2,308
per million in 1992 to 1,080 per million at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the mortality rate of babies decreased
from 86 per thousand to 37 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, 130,000 local maternity and child
care workers have received training and greatly raised their
competence for their service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
