<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Shares Close Lower in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong share prices
slumped by 25 percent in the year of 1997, as the key market index
closed at 10,722.76 points during the half-day session on New
Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
A year earlier on December 31, 1996, the Hang Seng Index
reached 13,451.45 points, a quarter higher than the year-end close
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip index fell 32.45 points, or 0.3 percent,
Wednesday from the previous close to end the year at 10,722.76
points.
</P>
<P>
The 33-member index surged 180.37 points in the first few
minutes of trading Wednesday morning to the day's high of
10,935.58 points, but lost ground later.
</P>
<P>
Turnover climbed up to 4.948 billion HK dollars (634 million
U.S. dollars) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As of December 19 this year, the market capitalization stood at
3,148 billion HK dollars (above 400 billion U.S. dollars), down
five percent from a year before but still putting the Stock
Exchange of Hong Kong (SEHK) well into the world's top ten
bourses.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover for the year reached 3,761 billion HK dollars
(482 billion U.S. dollars), 2.7 times that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
There are 658 listed companies on the SEHK, with 82 initial
public offerings in 1997. Fifteen more China's state-owned
enterprises, known as H shares, were listed in Hong Kong this
year, raising a total of 28.625 billion HK dollars (3.7 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
So far 39 H shares and more than 50 red chips (China-affiliated
and Hong Kong-registered companies) have gone public on the SEHK.
The market capitalization of these China-related companies
accounts for 18 percent of the total in the Hong Kong market.
</P>
</TEXT>
