<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
weaker Wednesday, trading quietly in a shortened session ahead of
the New Year's Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed weaker on the last day of trading
following another fall in the gold price Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 65.24 U.S. cents at midday
Wednesday, back from 65.48 late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A trader from Rothschild Australia said the slip in gold prices
fostered some bearish sentiment in the market.
</P>
<P>
"Gold prices are definitely weighing it down," he said.
</P>
<P>
The gold price was pressured by sharp U.S. equities gains and
research from Merrill Lynch predicting a bearish trend for gold in
the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
Compounding the world-wide loss of faith in gold, economic
meltdown in Asia and falling commodity prices present a grim
outlook for the New Year.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar will enter 1998 more than 14 U.S. cents
lower than its level a year ago, when it was trading at 79.46 U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank chief economist Craig James said the
Australian dollar fell just over 12 percent against its U.S.
counterpart during the past four months, while commodity prices
dropped almost 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
"How much of a surprise is the Australian dollar at 65 U.S.
cents when gold is just above 18 year lows, copper prices are at
four year lows, oil prices are near 2 year lows and aluminum
prices are near 12 month lows," he said.
</P>
<P>
James said the Australian dollar was likely to be mired around
65 U.S. cents to 67 U.S. cents for several months.
</P>
<P>
He said the dominating influence was the prospect of recession
in Australia's two largest export partners, Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The Asian currency crisis was now giving way to a debt crisis,
James said.
</P>
<P>
"Corporate bankruptcies will increase, unemployment will rise
and output will contract as the region undertakes painful
restructuring," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished the year at 84.76 Japanese yen,
from 85.04 Tuesday, and at 1.1672 German marks, from 1.1704.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
