<HEADLINE> Dialogue Urged to Solve Mozambican Emigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President
Joaquim Chissano has said that the problems arising from
Mozambicans emigrants to Swaziland should be solved through
dialogue between the two governments.
</P>
<P>
Chissano made the statement while meeting with some Mozambican
emigrants to Swaziland Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that he did not believe that Mozambicans have been
maltreated by senior leaders of Swaziland, saying that only a
handful of Swaziland people may have bad ideas about Mozambicans.
</P>
<P>
Some Mozambicans said that they have been arrested, beaten and
even called "dogs" in Swaziland, and urged the problems to be
discussed at the parliamentary meeting.
</P>
<P>
Chissano stressed that further study is needed to find out a
proper way to solve the problems, adding that it is not strange
for some Swaziland people to do so, as they might have thought
that foreigners have taken away their job opportunities.  
