<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close on Positive Note for New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
finished New Year's Eve trading on a stronger note following a
late rally fueled by positive leads from Tokyo and New York
Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones dealer Michael Baker said investor
interest in Telstra receipts ahead of the company's official
incorporation into the all ordinaries index on January 2 helped
the local bourse rally before closing at 13:05 (local time)
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It finished on a pretty good note," Baker said.
</P>
<P>
"The volume wasn't fantastic," he said, "but in a half day's
trade that's quite good."
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries closed up 15.1 points, or 0.58 percent, to
2616.5.
</P>
<P>
The share market has made small but definite gains throughout
the week as institutions indulge in their traditional practice of
end-of-year window dressing.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed up 28.9 points, or 0.65
percent, at 4475.9 while the all resources index inched up 3.7
points, or 0.33 percent, to finish at 1134.4.
</P>
<P>
Telstra Corporation's installment receipts were the most
heavily traded stock, trading up eight cents to 3.24 Australian
dollars on a turnover of 30.08 million shares worth 62.72 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector finished 39.3 points stronger at 5498.3,
with ANZ bank up 32 cents, or 3.26 percent, to close at 10.14
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other major banking stocks were also firmer with National
Australia Bank up 3.6 cents to 21.43 Australian dollars, Westpac
up 1.6 cents to 9.82 Australian dollars while Commonwealth Bank of
Australia was steady at 17.60 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resource leader BHP lost 11 cents to 14.25 Australian dollars,
and Rio Tinto climbed 21.3 cents to 17.90 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished 12.4 points up, or 1.23 percent, at
1017.5 despite a fall in the value of gold bullion on the previous
evening. Gold bullion in Sydney opened at 290.35 U.S. dollars,
down slightly from Tuesday night's local close of 291.10 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
At 15:29 (local time) Wednesday spot gold bullion was trading
down 1.70 U.S. dollars at 289.15 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover at 13:40 (local time) was 173.55 million,
valued at 359.1 million U.S. dollars, with rises outnumbering
falls 504 to 332. 
</P>
