<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Former Pak Defense Minister Running for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Former defense minister
Aftab Shahban Mirani, the nominee of the major opposition Pakistan
People's Party (PPP) in Wednesday's presidential elections, is
seen as a worthwhile, though not the most hopeful, candidate.
</P>
<P>
Given the thin strength of the PPP in the federal parliament
and four provincial assemblies, Mirani seems to be in no position
to compete with the most possible winner, Rafiq Tarar, candidate
of the ruling Pakistan Muslim League (N).
</P>
<P>
However, Mirani, a member of the National Assembly, is still
seen as a worthwhile candidate in light of his noticeable
political career.
</P>
<P>
Mirani hails from a political family. His father Ghulam Kadir
Shahban Mirani was one of the three elected members of the Indian
Central Legislative Assembly from Sindh in pre-independence era.
</P>
<P>
He started his political career as elected president of
Shikarpur Municipality. Before he was elected to the National
Assembly in 1990, he had served as chief minister of Sindh
province for a long time.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, he was awarded the PPP ticket to contest election for
the National Assembly, wherefrom he succeeded with a majority.
Later he was appointed defense minister by then prime minister
Benazir Bhutto.
</P>
<P>
Mirani, who speaks fluent English, Sindhi and Urdu, has
represented Pakistan at various international seminars and
conferences.
</P>
<P>
Being an agriculturist, Mirani had attended formal courses in
modern farm management and agriculture in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mirani is married and has one son and three daughters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
