<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, South Pacific Nations Forge Closer Ties (1) --by Liu Dongkai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- China and South Pacific
nations have maintained steady momentum in developing bilateral
relations, scoring notable breakthroughs in many areas over the
past year, according to observers here.
</P>
<P>
This year has witnessed increased exchange visits between
leaders from China and South Pacific nations. Senior Chinese
officials visiting the region included Zhu Rongji and Li Ruihuan,
two of seven members in China's highest leadership group--the
Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC). Zhu and Li were
the highest-ranking Chinese officials visiting the region in a
number of years.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from most major countries in the South Pacific visited
China during 1997, including Australian Prime Minister John Howard
and Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer, former New Zealand Prime
Minister James Bolger and former Deputy Prime Minister Winston
Peters, Vanuatu Prime Minister Rialuth Serge Vohor, Palau
President Kuniwo Nakamura and Fijian Minister of Foreign Affairs
and Trade Berenado Vunibobo.
</P>
<P>
Frequent visits by high-ranking officials and the smooth
operation of bilateral consulting mechanisms strengthened
relations between China and nations in the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
China established diplomatic relations with the Cook Islands on
July 25, thereby raising the number of the region's nations having
diplomatic ties with China to 10.
</P>
<P>
Local foreign affairs experts point out that China and South
Pacific nations, neighbors in the Asia Pacific Region, share a
broad range of mutual interests and either common or similar views
on many major issues.
</P>
<P>
Prior to China's resumption of sovereignty over Hong Kong on
July 1, Australia and New Zealand took the lead amongst western
countries by announcing their decisions to send represtatives to
all ceremonies marking the establishment of the Government of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR). Government
officials from the two countries repeatedly made it clear they
would contribute to the smooth transfer of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
During the April meeting of the United Nations Commission on
Human Rights, Australia refused to sponsor an anti-China motion
tabled by a small group of countries. Instead, Australia sent
representatives to Beijing in August to initiate a dialog with
China on bilateral relations and human rights.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Chinese Foreign Ministry note that
strengthening relations between China and South Pacific nations is
in the mutual interests of all sides and highly beneficial for
promoting regional stability and development.
</P>
<P>
China has maintained good momentum in its relations with
Australia and New Zealand, the two largest countries in the South
Pacific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
