<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second-Hand Vehicles Get a Second Life in Impoverished Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Guizhou Province, a backward
economy in southwest China, is creative in aiding its impoverished
regions by giving automobiles a new life.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 235 second-hand taxis and shuttle buses have been
overhauled by the provincial public transport society and handed
over to impoverished prefectures free or at a price of 3,000-4,000
yuan (361-481 U.S. dollars). An additional 600 automobiles
reportedly will be recycled in the same way by June.
</P>
<P>
Headed by the the construction department of the province two
years ago, the plot now has been consummated with a complete
managing system. No accident due to quality problems has been
reported on these vehicles.
</P>
<P>
With the province's assistance, eight counties where no public
traffic existed now have their own traffic companies.
</P>
<P>
Kaili City, located in a mountainous area and whose bus firm
had been on the verge of bankruptcy, also received 67
automobiles. Its fare income for this year has reached 2.8 million
yuan (337,000 U.S. dollars), compared with 800,000 yuan (96,000
U.S. dollars) two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Auto maintenance and infrastructure building in these areas
have been boosted along with the improvement of traffic
conditions. Carts, rickshaws and unqualified motorcycles and
diesel-driven three-wheeled cars are being removed from the
streets.
</P>
<P>
Vehicle transfers has also quickened the step of automobiles
renewal in large cities. Guiyang, capital of the province, has
been encouraging the renewal of taxis with more famous domestic
brands such as Cherade (Xiali), Fukang Citroen, Jetta and
Santana.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
