<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Rafiq Tarar, Hot Favorite for Pakistan's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Senator Rafiq Tarar,
presidential nominee of the ruling Pakistan Muslim League (N)
(PML-N), is tipped as a hot favorite for the presidency in
Wednesday's election.
</P>
<P>
Given the overwhelming parliamentary strength of the PML-N, the
68-year-old Rafiq is almost certain to win the presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
Rafiq's nomination as presidential candidate by the PML-N and
its allied parties, which hold a two-thirds majority in the
217-member National Assembly, had come as a surprise to all, as
his name was not among those who were expected to occupy the
presidential office.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's presidential polls are taking place as a result of
the resignation of President Farooq Leghari early this month at
the climax of a worst-ever constitutional crisis involving the
government and the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
According to the Election Commission, whosoever secures 51
percent of the 476 electoral college votes, or at least 239 votes,
will be declared next president of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
A former judge of the Supreme Court, Rafiq, who hails from a
relatively humble origin, is noted for his legal scholarship,
honesty and devotion to justice.
</P>
<P>
Rafiq, who was born on November 2, 1929, got his law degree
from Punjab University Law College in 1951 and then started his
legal practice.
</P>
<P>
In 1974, he was elevated to the High Court of Lahore, capital
of Punjab province, and served as a member of the Election
Commission of Pakistan from 1980. He was appointed Chief Justice
of the Lahore High Court on December 13, 1989.
</P>
<P>
Rafiq was elevated to the Supreme Court in January 1991, and
was a member of the 11-person bench which restored the first
government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
He retired in October 1994 and was elected a senator on a
ticket of Pakistan Muslim League (N) in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
The nomination papers of Rafiq were first rejected by the
Election Commission for his alleged remarks ridiculing the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
However, he has his name cleared from the Lahore High Court
which Tuesday allowed him to contest the presidential election. If
he makes it, he will be the first former judge to become the head
of state of Pakistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
