<HEADLINE> Automobiles in Chinese Capital to Use Lead-Free Gasoline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital Beijing
will ban the using and selling of gasoline that contains lead as
of January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The measure is taken by the municipal government to reduce air
pollution in the city.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Environmental Protection and Industry and Commerce
bureaus issued a circular over the weekend, demanding all the
filling stations in urban and rural Beijing to sell lead-free
gasoline from the start of next year. Violators will face penalty.
</P>
<P>
Beijing began to promote the use of lead-free gasoline last
June in eight of its 18 districts and counties.
</P>
<P>
The city has been plagued by air pollution in recent years
because of auto emission and coal consumption. It has become one
of the seriously polluted cities in the world, according to the
United Nations Environment Program.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a member of the Standing Committee of the National
People Congress spoke at the committee's 29th meeting, calling
for an immediate action to reduce air pollution in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
