<HEADLINE> Hunan Successful in Developing Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A campaign to promote
broadly-based development in agriculture has made great strides in
Hunan, an inland province in central China.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government launched the campaign in 1989
involving 13 cities and prefectures -- 71 counties and state-owned
farms -- with an investment of 2.15 billion yuan (270 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
With the investment, the province has improved more than
420,000 hectares of low- and medium-yield fields, upgraded 54,000
hectares of wasteland and planted trees on 140,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the comprehensive agricultural development zones
have added 1.835 million tons of grain, 14,600 tons of cotton,
113,400 tons of vegetable oil crops and 341,700 tons of meat since
the operation of the campaign. The per capita net income of
farmers in the zones has increased 364 yuan since 1989.
</P>
<P>
The comprehensive development of agriculture in the province
has aroused farmers' enthusiasm, upgraded technology and set up a
group of modern production bases to propel the economy, said Pang
Daomo, vice-governor of the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
