<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Brief History of Pakistan's Presidential Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is holding
presidential election Wednesday to elect the country's ninth
president since its independence in 1947.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing presidential election is being held after
resignation from the presidency by Farooq Leghari on December 2 at
the peak of a worst-ever constitutional crisis in this South Asian
nation.
</P>
<P>
Under Pakistan's Constitution, the president is not only the
head of state but also represents the unity of the Islamic
Republic.
</P>
<P>
It is constitutionally stipulated that any Muslim Pakistani
citizen enrolled as a voter, not less than 45 years of age and
qualified to be elected as Member of the National Assembly, can
become president.
</P>
<P>
The first election to the office of president was conducted by
the Speaker, Constituent Assembly, under the 1956 Constitution.
Iskander Mirza, being the only candidate for this election, was
declared elected unopposed.
</P>
<P>
The poll for the second election to the office of president was
held on January 2, 1965 under the 1962 Constitution. Field Marshal
Muhammad Ayub Khan was declared elected as president.
</P>
<P>
After the promulgation of the 1973 Constitution, the first
election to the office of president was held on August 10, 1973.
This presidential race was won by Fazal Elahi of the Pakistan
People's Party against the opposition's joint candidate Amirzada
Khan.
</P>
<P>
As a consequence of referendum held on December 19, 1984,
General Zia-ul Haq was elected president of Pakistan. After his
death on August 17, 1988, then Chairman of the Senate Ghulam Ishaq
Khan took over as acting president, who was elected to the office
of president on December 12, 1988.
</P>
<P>
The political instability and crisis that engulfed Pakistan
from February/March 1993 due to strained relations between the
president and the prime minister finally resulted in the
dissolution of the National Assembly on April 18, 1993.
</P>
<P>
However, the Supreme Court set aside the order of dissolution
of the National Assembly and restored it on May 26, 1993. The
political situation thereafter further aggravated and, ultimately
on the advice of the prime minister, the National Assembly was
again dissolved on July 18, 1993.
</P>
<P>
The second dissolution of the National Assembly in 1993 was
followed by the resignation of President Ghulam Ishaq Khan on July
18 the same year.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Senate Wasim Sajjad then became acting
president until Farooq Leghari was elected to the office of
President in November 11, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Farooq Leghari tendered his resignation from the presidency on
December 2, 1997 after the four-month-long nerve-wracking tussle
between the government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and the
judiciary led by then Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah reached its
climax.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Collect Data on Opium Cultivation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar will launch a
nation-wide campaign to collect baseline data on opium cultivation
and drug addicts beginning January 1, 1998, a senior Myanmar
official told a press briefing here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The three-month campaign will be carried out with mobilization
of the entire population in Myanmar including ethnic minorities to
correctly assess the opium yield and addicts in the country, said
Colonel Kyaw Thein, head of the Office of Strategic Studies of the
Myanmar Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A wide gap exists in the forecasts on the hectarage and
production of opium made by Myanmar and the United States, he
pointed out, arguing that Myanmar's opium cultivation data are
based on actual ground survey and calculation, while the U.S. data
are based on satellite images.
</P>
<P>
The national-level statistical data compilation is initiated
following a recent reformation of the country's Central Committee
for Drug Abuse Control (CCDAC), he added.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that the Myanmar authorities destroyed 33
opium refineries in Shan state of the country in 1997, seizing a
total of 9,800 kg narcotic drugs, including 1,396 kg heroin and
7,651 kg opium in the country in the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
