<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 150 U.S. Police Killed on Duty in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- At least 150 police
officers were killed on duty in the United States this year, up 27
percent from last year, the National Association of Chiefs of
Police said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Association officials said California had the highest number of
deaths, with 18 reported so far, followed by Texas with 10.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the death toll was uncharacteristically low and this
year's figure is similar to the years before.
</P>
<P>
"What we are seeing is a return to typically tragic levels of
officer deaths, consistent with what we've seen throughout this
decade," said Morton Feldman, executive vice president of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
Between 1990 and 1996, 1,111 U.S. officers lost their lives
while on duty, or an average of 159 annually.
</P>
<P>
"Regrettably, the 1996 figure apparently was nothing more than
a statistical anomaly and not an indicator that officer deaths are
following the general U.S. trend toward decreasing violent crime,"
Feldman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
