<HEADLINE> Yeltsin on Russia's Major Achievements in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said here Tuesday that Russia has scored a number of major
successes in 1997 in the economic, political and diplomatic fields.
</P>
<P>
In a year-end interview with major Russian press organizations
in Moscow, Yeltsin said that after years of decline, Russia's
economy had stabilized and even registered a growth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Although the economic growth, though limited but statistically
significant, signaled a recovery of the Russian economy, he noted.
</P>
<P>
It was encouraging that the number of districts which witnessed
industrial output growth had risen to 30 in 1997 from four in
1996, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Russian president stressed the need to continue
developing national economy instead of resting on the laurels of
achieved successes.
</P>
<P>
On the political situation, Yeltsin said there emerged a
momentum of national harmony and reconciliation in Russia in
1997. Relations among government organs at different levels have
greatly improved.
</P>
<P>
He called on local governments to strengthen regular and
constructive dialogues and to wipe out the legacy of confrontation
left over by history.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Russia's diplomatic achievements in 1997, Yeltsin
cited the establishment of the Russia-Belarus alliance, the
improvement of Russia-Ukraine ties, the entry of Russia into a
number of international organizations, the consolidation of
Russia's equal partnership with the United States and other
developed countries, as well as the improved ties between Russia
and Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Particularly citing the progress made in the development of
Russia-China ties, Yeltsin said the settlement of nearly all the
border issues between Russia and China is significant not only for
the two countries, but also for Asia as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president admitted that although Russia has made
progress in many fields in 1997, there was still much room for
improvement.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the Russian government will concentrate its
efforts on revitalizing the economy in 1998 and work out new plans
in this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
