<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Presidential Election Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A secret ballot poll to
elect the ninth president of Pakistan started Wednesday at 10.00
a.m.
</P>
<P>
The election, which is to conclude till 3 p.m., is also being
held simultaneously in the four Provincial Assemblies of Punjab,
Sindh, Balochistan and North West Frontier provinces.
</P>
<P>
According to the Election Commission, the total electoral
college votes are 476, including 87 Senators, 217 members of the
National Assembly and 43 votes of each of the four provincial
assemblies. A candidate must poll at least 51 percent of the total
or 239 votes to win.
</P>
<P>
The contestant to emerge successful in the elections is likely
to be sworn in as Pakistan's next president soon after the
announcement of the results, the Election Commission said, adding
the counting of the votes will start right after the close of the
polling.
</P>
<P>
In all, seven candidates are in the run for the presidential
race, with the government fielding Rafiq Tarar, the opposition
represented by Aftab Shaaban Mirani from the Pakistan People's
Party, Maulana Shirani from Jamiat-e-Ulema and Zafarullah Jamali
contesting as an independent.
</P>
<P>
Rafiq, the official nominee of the ruling Pakistan Muslim
League (Nawaz) (PML-N), appears to be the most possible winner as
the PML-N and its allied parties enjoy a favorable two thirds
majority in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's elections were required as President Farooq Leghari
resigned on December 2 when a worst ever constitutional crisis
involving the government and the judiciary reached its climax.
Leghari had refused to sign a reference against Chief Justice
Sajjad Ali Shah at that time as required by the government led by
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Under Pakistan's constitution, a new president has to be
elected in 30 days starting from the president-in-power's
resignation is accepted by the speaker of the National Assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
