<HEADLINE> Thai Economy May See Zero Growth in 1997: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to record
zero economic growth for 1997 and the prospects for recovery next
year are uncertain, according to a year-end report of the Bank of
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
All the key economic indicators showed signs of slowdown since
the beginning of 1997 as a result of the financial crisis,
according to the report available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the first 10 months of the year, the industrial production
index expanded only 1.6 percent, and private investment grew only
0.2 percent, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
In the 10-month period, exports growth reached 3.7 percent in
U.S. dollar terms, or 20.7 percent in baht terms.
</P>
<P>
The current account will post a deficit of 3 percent of the
gross domestic product (GDP) this year, totaling about 85 billion
baht (1.8 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The economic slowdown has reduced Thais' purchasing power. In
the period under review, retail sales at department stores plunged
4.7 percent, while automobile sales plummeted by 15.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
As to the prospects for 1998, the central bank was not certain
as to when the economy will bottom out. A recovery will depend on
the speed with which the financial institutions are tackled, said
Kleo-thong Hetrakul, director of the central bank's Economic
Research Department.
</P>
<P>
"If the policy framework is implemented successfully,
confidence will quickly return," The Nation Wednesday quotes
Kleo-thong as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
