<HEADLINE> Shanghai Residents Care for Air Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Air quality is the first
consideration for more and more residents in Shanghai when they
purchase houses.
</P>
<P>
"Many residents inquire about the air pollution index in
the area where they plans to buy houses," said Liu Hong, an
official with the Municipal Environmental Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
She added that she receives an average of 80 phones a
day.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has been issuing weekly reports on air quality since
June 5, and many have since begun to care for the urban air
condition as much as the weather.
</P>
<P>
"Many complained for the serious air pollution in the areas
they live. They write to us and ask the government to take
steps," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
The city has witnessed a "warm winter" this year. The slow wind
speed has led to the increase of the air pollution index.
"Residents care very much for this and ask us to show their
concern for the deterioration of the air quality," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
"Although the air-quality report brings pressure to us, it
enhances the city's efforts for pollution control," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
The city has banned the sale of lead gasoline since December 1,
and it plans to transform its 400,000 taxis and a number of the
buses into liquefied natural gas automobiles in five years, in a
bid to improve the city's air quality.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
