<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Needs More Loans: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will need at least
another 8 billion U.S. dollars in fresh loans next year to bolster
its foreign exchange reserves and help stabilize the sagging Thai
baht, according to The Nation newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The suggestion, made by Chalongphob Sussangkarn, president of
the Thailand Development Research Institute, reflects a growing
school of opinion at home and abroad that the 17.2 billion dollar
bailout package arranged by the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
is far from adequate to tackle the country's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chalongphob said the central bank's foreign exchange reserves
have been reducing significantly in spite of the IMF's package
because foreign investors are selling off the baht for the U.S.
dollar for fear the reserves will not be enough to meet the
country's huge debt obligations.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's private debts have reached 70 billion dollars, about
half of which are believed to have short-term maturity.
</P>
<P>
Chalongphob said the baht will continue to come under pressure
next year because investors believe short-term debts will continue
to rise.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that once the reserves of the central
bank have strengthened, confidence will return to the Thai
economy.
</P>
<P>
He also believes that an 8 billion additional credit will help
prop up the baht from 47 to 42 against the U.S. dollar next year.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
