<HEADLINE> Pakistan Holds Presidential Election Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan will elect its
seventh head of the state Wednesday to fill the vacancy of the
presidential slot following President Farooq Leghari's resignation
early this month.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission announced Tuesday that the polling for
election to the office of the president would be held Wednesday
from 10:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m. (local time) simultaneously in the
Parliament and all the four provincial assemblies.
</P>
<P>
The contestant to emerge successful in the elections is likely
to be sworn in as Pakistan's next president soon after the
announcement of the results, the Election Commission said, adding
the counting of the votes will start right after the close of the
polling.
</P>
<P>
Rafiq Tarar, official presidential nominee of the ruling
Pakistan Muslim League (Nawaz) (PML-N), appears to be the most
possible winner among all the seven candidates who are in the run
for the presidential race. The PML-N and its allied parties enjoy
a two-thirds majority in the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's presidential election will be the seventh Pakistan
has held in 50 years. The first such election was held in 1956.
</P>
<P>
This election is being held as a result of the stepping down of
President Farooq Leghari on December 2 when a worst ever
constitutional crisis involving the government and the judiciary
reached its climax. Leghari had refused to sign a reference
against Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah at that time as required by
the government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Under Pakistan's Constitution, a new president has to be
elected in 30 days after the president-in-power's resignation is
accepted by the speaker of the National Assembly.  
</P>
