<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga Tuesday asked the southern youth not to be misled by
the Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna (JVP), an organization that had
staged an armed rebellion in 1971 to capture power, news reaching
here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president made the call while attending a rally in the
southern city of Galle.
</P>
<P>
She noted the JVP, also called the People's Revolutionary
Front, seemed to be raising its head again.
</P>
<P>
In the 1971 youth rebellion, the JVP held several areas of the
country for almost one month and in 1988 they shocked the nation
again by assassinating several VIPs.
</P>
<P>
The movement met a major setback when all key leaders but one
were arrested and killed in 1989 by the then government under the
United National Party. But it regained its momentum in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga also said at the rally that the constitutional
reforms of her government was the only solution to the present
crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
An ethnic war has been going on for 14 years in the north and
east of the country between the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
and the government troops.  
