<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Tighten Indigenization Norms for Car Makers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 31 (Xinhua)-- The Indian government will
take measures to tighten indigenization norms for the car
manufacturing sector in the country, Commerce Ministry sources
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry is expected to issue a detailed
notification this week outlining the indigenization norms to be
followed by each car manufacturer for obtaining import licenses
for completely knocked down (CKD) kits under the recently
announced automobile policy.
</P>
<P>
The new notification will require each ancillary vendor to a
particular domestic car project to declare the import content of
its product in writing.
</P>
<P>
This declaration will then be taken into account to calculate
the net import content of the specific car project.
</P>
<P>
The government will take into account the import content of
each auto-ancillary vendor of a car company in order to calculate
the indigenization level for the entire car project.
</P>
<P>
At present, the vendor's import content is not taken into
consideration while calculating the net indigenization on the
engine.
Under the proposed norms, the vendor's import content will be
taken into account.
</P>
<P>
By using this method, the government hopes to plug a loophole
which car companies can use to show high indigenization levels by
outsourcing from domestic auto vendors, which in turn import from
overseas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
