<HEADLINE> China Able to Design Nuclear Power Plants with Pressurized Water Reactors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- China is now able to
independently design nuclear power plants with pressurized water
reactors.
</P>
<P>
This marks the improvement in China's self-designing capability
of nuclear power plants, said Chinese experts at a working
conference held here recently by the China Nuclear Power Institute.
</P>
<P>
They said that China expects to use nuclear power plants that
are designed, manufactured, built and operated by the Chinese
themselves.
</P>
<P>
China built the 300,000-kw Qishan Nuclear Power Plant with
pressurized water reactors in 1991, the first of its kind in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Around the turn of the century, China will complete building
the second and third phases at Qinshan and the Lianyungang Nuclear
Power Plant in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The eight generating units needed at Qinshan and Lianyungang
will have a generating capacity of 600,000 to 900,000 kw each and
they will be built at home, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
China has acquired the tehnology to design and produce some 400
softwares of pressurized water reactors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China is also working on perfecting the standards
for nuclear power plants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Soccer Laments Sixth Abortive World Cup Attempt (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese soccer fans have
been tantalized to the worst as their footballers played their
best in an abortive sixth straight attempt towards the World Cup
finals in the past year full of sorrows and sadness.
</P>
<P>
After squeezing into the top 10 in Asia, China was nevertheless
kept away from booking any of the three or four Asian tickets
allocated by FIFA for the quadrennial soccer summit.
</P>
<P>
Being an overall sports power in Asia, China was still on the
way to make its footsteps in the men's soccer world as its
footballers have a lonely silver to their credit from the Asian
Games in Hiroshima in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In the Asian qualifying tournament, China was lucky enough to
avoid its neighboring chief rivals of South Korea and Japan after
being pitched in Group A, together with four West Asian nations of
Iran, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and Qatar.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese squad, under the orchestration of a dozen
of coaches and advisors, was plummeted to the mud with 11 points
from three wins, two draws and three loses after a morale-boosting
warm-up voyage of three wins and one draw in England.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the final clashes in the Asian qualifying tournament,
the Chinese players and even their coaches nourished a dream of
making the debut in the World Cup finals as they boasted of the
players' speed which saw a tough quarterfinal loss 4-3 against
eventual winners of Saudi Arabia in the Asian Cup last December,
and a deserved draw with Iran in a warm-up.
</P>
<P>
Yet, their cautious and optimistic spirits were blown away as
the Chinese eleven were thrashed 3-8 on aggregate by runners-up
Iran, and even sunk 3-4 by the group tailers Qatar despite their
overall win of 2-1 against group leaders Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
"Our players, for the most of the time, were at loss on the
pitch because no specific tactics were fixed for the squad and the
players ran to and from at large which resulted in many a unmarked
spots in the back court," said former head coach of the national
squad Nian Weisi in a column in the local media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
