<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Soccer Laments Sixth Abortive World Cup Attempt (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese footballers were teased to the most when they lost
the opener 4-2 from a comfortable 2-0 advantage. After a lukewarm
1-1 tie in Doha with Qatar, the Chinese scored only seven points
against Iran's 12 and Saudi's nine.
</P>
<P>
With three games remained, China theoretically still had the
chance for the top spot in the Group after Saudi Arabia was held a
goalless draw by Kuwait, and at least could settle for a runner-up
playoff with two wins and a draw on goal differentials.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the worse moment came when the Chinese saw their hopes
evaporated when the Chinese squad squandered its earlier lead on
home turf as the Qatars scored three goals in 15 minutes for a 3-2
away win.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Qi Wusheng, who was booed by the agitated
fans, fielded off the questions saying that "my players were not
quick enough for the control in the midfield. We failed in our
counter attacks and lost our composure."
</P>
<P>
After the defeat, the Chinese side was virtually out of the
contention for its outing for the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
Peter Vellapan, general secretary of the Asian Football
Association, commented later that "they (the Chinese footballers)
are not as enterprising as pro players in German League. They
played the first halves of the most games with consistency and
strength. But in the second half, you might think you were
watching an amateur team instead of a national squad."
</P>
<P>
Back to home, the Chinese clubs were seemingly full of energy
and geniuses as Dalian Wanda, triple winner of China's soccer
league, secured its third national title in advance with five
rounds remained and even attained an unpredecented feat of 55
straight wins.
</P>
<P>
Wanda, who had its winning streak snapped by runner-up Shanghai
Shenhua in the last round of the league, also moved into the
quarter-finals of the Asian Champions Tournament after trouncing
Na Huan of Hong Kong, China, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
League third-placer Beijing Guo'an also made its quarter-final
debut in the Asian Cup Winners' Cup, eliminating the Japanese Cup
winners Verdy Kawasaki 3-0 on aggregate.
</P>
<P>
Guo'an, who humiliated Shanghai Shenhua 9-1 in a July league
match, then became the first club to retain the Chinese Football
Association Cup title by defeating Shenhua 2-1 on December 28.
</P>
<P>
It goes without saying that the victories of the clubs only
reflect the immaturity and lack of competitiveness of the Chinese
footballers who again pin their hopes upon the 2002 World Cup
finals and even later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
