<HEADLINE> Migrants Come to Spend Winter in Shanghai Safari </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- With winter gradually taking
over the northern hemisphere, thousands of migrants have found a
haven from the winter chill in Shanghai Safari.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of October, more than 1,000 black-crowned
night-herons and hundreds of mallards and other wild ducks have
come to live in the safari, said Zhang Cizu, deputy general
manager of the safari.
</P>
<P>
Being wading and natatorial birds, the herons and wild ducks
live in or beside the water. Some even brave the reed marshes in
the living quarters of tigers and cheetahs, and the birds and
their feline neighbors are so models of good neighborliness by
keeping a peaceful co-existence with each other.
</P>
<P>
The migrants usually find their own foods, and they have
another food source in the abundant feeds provided for resident
birds.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the abundant food and favorable environment, explain
a safari worker, the herons and wild ducks have come here also to
hide from attacks from humans outside.
</P>
<P>
It is recorded that only a dozen black-headed night-herons came
to spend the winter in the Shanghai Safari when it was open to
public in 1995. Last winter, about a hundred herons visited, and
the heron population soared to more than 1,000 this winter.
</P>
<P>
The migrants will fly back to the north in March and April next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
