<HEADLINE> Economy in Southwest China Catching Up With National Average </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Guizhou, an impoverished
province in southwest China, has caught up with the national
average in economic growth, according to a high provincial
official.
</P>
<P>
Its gross domestic product (GDP) this year is expected to
increase 9 percent over last year and inflation should be less
than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
This would be the first time the backward province has kept
pace with the national economy, said Liu Fangren, secretary of the
Guizhou Provincial Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, Guizhou will reach a total revenue of 10
billion yuan (1.2 billion US dollars) this year, up 14 percent
over 1996, an all-time record in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that the industrial output this year will
increase by 14.8 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
Grain output was 10.26 million tons this year, a 2.3 percent
increase over 1996. Meanwhile, the output of flue-cured tobacco,
rapeseed and meat is also on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The sales of township-run enterprises in the province have
risen by 31 percent, compared to 1996, according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
With the aim of shaking off poverty and embarking on the road
of economic sustainable development, the provincial government has
attached importance to agriculture and infrastructure
construction, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
A new, modern airport has been built in Guiyang, the provincial
capital, and a 155.3-km highway connects Guiyang and Zunyi.
</P>
<P>
The province's export-oriented economy has made great progress
with improvements made in the basic facilities, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province has utilized 138 million
U.S. dollars of overseas funds this year, a 30 percent increase
over 1996, and exports have grown by 10 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
