<HEADLINE> North China's Laid-offs Doing As Well In Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of
laid-off workers in money-losing state enterprises turn to private
businesses, and the fact is that many of them are just doing as
well.
</P>
<P>
One example is Han Kuiju in the capital city of Shijiazhuang,
Hebei Province. The 41-year-old ex-serviceman lost his job early
in 1988. But now he runs a garage, with 30 laid-offs working for
him.
</P>
<P>
A technician in a state enterprise, Han felt ill at ease doing
private business at the beginning. He tried to look for another
post in state institutions or enterprises, but in vain. This
forced him to make a career independently.
</P>
<P>
So he borrowed some money from friends and relatives and
started a garage to repair imported cars, which he found began to
flood into the country. He hired some skilled mechanics and
purchased advanced equipment for his garage.
</P>
<P>
Accurate market information and good service have brought him
more and more business, and profits as well. Now the garage has
grown into a vehicle maintenance center, graded as second-class by
local department of communications.
</P>
<P>
Hu Ruixiang of Baoding city is another example. Crowding
parents at primary schools' gates reminded Hu of setting up a
fetch-and-send team to take over the responsibility. So he did,
and employed more than 20 other laid-off workers to do the job,
making good money.
</P>
<P>
More than 130,000 laid-offs in Hebei Province have entered the
private sector, and governments and departments concerned have
adopted some favorable policies to promote the effort, according
to the provincial Administration Bureau for Industry and
Commerce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
