<HEADLINE> Prefecture Turns Sandy Soil into Productive Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The once harsh and adverse
conditions of Yulin Prefecture in northwestern Shaanxi Province
have been conquered and the prefecture turned into a grain base.
</P>
<P>
Major Chinese newspapers have run front-page stories about the
success of water and soil conservation, ecological farming and
tree-planting in the northern part of the province.
</P>
<P>
Yulin is located between the Muus Desert and the Loess Plateau,
a transit area where there was little vegetation. Local villages
and farmers were threatened by shifting sands.
</P>
<P>
The vegetation coverage in Yulin area has been raised from 1.8
percent in the early 1950s to 38.9 percent this year, and the
shifting sand dunes have diminished sharply.
</P>
<P>
The sandy Yulin Prefecture has been able to convert 400,000
hectares of the 533,000 hectare sandy area into high-yield
farmland which now produces 15,000 kg of grain per-hectare.
</P>
<P>
Governor Cheng Andong of Shaanxi Province said: "Although the
environment in the northwest is vulnerable, we are confident that
it will be improved greatly in the near future."
</P>
<P>
Sources show that one-ninth of China's domain is desert, mainly
in northwestern areas. Thousands of hectares of farmland are
endangered annually by the deserts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
