<HEADLINE> Parcel Bomb Defused in Southern Sri Lankan City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A bomb disposal unit of the
Sri Lankan Army Tuesday defused a parcel bomb sent to a police
officer who arrested nine Tamil rebel suspects involved in
Sunday's truck-bomb explosion in the southern city of Galle.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was defused at the Kalavanchikudi Post Office in Galle
Tuesday morning and nobody was hurt.
</P>
<P>
The parcel had been addressed to police officer L.G. Gunaratne,
who was responsible for the arrest of the suspects.
</P>
<P>
The 40kg parcel aroused suspicion when it was received at the
post office. The postmaster informed police of the suspicious
parcel, which later was found to be a bomb.
</P>
<P>
The truck-bomb exploded at around 02:30 Sunday morning 200
meters away from a major navy base in Galle, a city some 115 km
south of the capital Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Three occupants of the truck, believed to be rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), were killed in the
explosion, which also destroyed some surrounding buildings.
</P>
</TEXT>
