<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Secluded Islands Offer Safe Habitat for Birds in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Seventeen secluded bird islands,
mostly located in the middle of lakes, have been found in the
Tibet Autonomous Region, and they have become the safe habitat or
virtually "heaven" of the birds.
</P>
<P>
Through a six-year survey, Chinese experts found that Tibet has
more birds islands than previously thought. Most of the 17 bird
islands, each with an area of one hectare, are scattered far and
wide on the lakes at 4,200-5,000 meters high above sea level,
according to Liu Wulin, a wild-animal expert.
</P>
<P>
Tibet boasts most of the lakes in China, with 612 of one square
meter or larger.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the bird islands are dotted in the lakes of the
northern and southern Tibet Plateau, because the environment there
is very monotonous," Liu said, "therefore the birds have to go to
the islands to seek both shelter and food."
</P>
<P>
Thousands of birds dwell on the islands, including rare species
such as brown-headed sea gulls. Liu said there is an average of
one or two rare birds, or 10 sea gulls, for every square meter of
island. The birds substitute mainly on fish in the lakes.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that these islands are untraversed regions where
land foes are kept off and there is sufficient fish for the birds
to live on.
</P>
<P>
Because of the vast lake area in Tibet, Liu noted, many such
islands have not been discovered and more bird finds are possible.
</P>
<P>
"It is of vital importance to protect these islands and do more
in-depth research," one expert said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
