<HEADLINE> China Ocean Shipping (Group) co. Signs Memo with Custom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The China Ocean Shipping
(Group) Co. (Cosco) is developing its intermodal transportation
buiness by co-operating with the customs office, today's China
Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Its subordinate, Cosco Guangzhou International Intermodal Co.
Ltd, or CIIC (Guangzhou) Ltd, signed a memorandum of understanding
Tuesday with the Huangpu Customs Office in Guangzhou. The memo
concerned the container international intermodal transportation
operation.
</P>
<P>
"Signing such a memorandum, the first of its kind in
Guangzhou, ... will boost foreign trade transportation in
Guangzhou and in south China," said Fang Meigang, deputy
administrator of the Huangpu Custom Office.
</P>
<P>
According to the memorandum, CIIC (Guangzhou) Ltd. will apply
customs clearance and ship cargo exclusively for foreign trade
enterprises with good reputations, offer timely information
related to foreign trade and smuggling clues to customs office and
aid the customs office's supervision and inspection work.
</P>
<P>
The Huangpu Custom office will simplify the customs clearance
procedures for highly reputed enterprises that entrust CIIC
(Guangzhou) Ltd. and give support to CIIC (Guangzhou) Ltd. in
business operation of container international intermodal with
Hong Kong and Shenzhen's Shekou as the entrepots.
</P>
<P>
Container intermodal transportation is the very trend of
international transportation development and one of China's key
transportation projects highlighted in the ongoing Ninth Five-Year
Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
The practice is the integrated transportation system consisting
of dual transportation modes: by river and by sea, by railway and
by sea, by air and by water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
