<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Promote Production of Import Substitutes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 31 (Xinhua) - Myanmar leader Lieutenant
General Tin Oo has urged local entrepreneurs to boost production
of import substitutes and promote exports.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with members of the Myanmar Chamber of Commerce
and Industry here Tuesday, Tin Oo, second secretary of the Myanmar
State Peace and Development Council, stressed the need to reduce
reliance on imported goods in the country's consumption and
production sectors, the official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the private sector involvement increased to about 76
percent in the gross domestic product due to the greater role of
the market economic system, citing the ever increasing ratio of
the private sector in production, services and trade.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Chamber of Commerce and Industry to serve as a
 bridge between the government and merchants and entrepreneurs and
to strengthen the economic relations between the foreign
organizations and domestic ones.
</P>
<P>
He also called for development of the country's economy,
inviting participation in terms of technical know-how and
investments from sources inside the country and abroad.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, a total of 22,813 private
enterprises had been registered by the end of September this year.
Among them are 1,118 foreign companies and branches, 121
Myanmar-foreign joint ventures and 34 chambers of commerce.
</P>
</TEXT>
