<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Seeks Control on Kurdish Inflow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 30 (Xinhua)-- Italy is negotiating with Turkey
and other European Union member states to seek effective measures
to control the inflow of Kurdish refugees into Italy, Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Interior Minister Giorgio Napolitano at the
Lower House, Dini said he is confident Turkey will be cooperative
over a problem which not only involves Italy, but also "all
Europe", the Italian news agency Ansa reported.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Kurdish immigrants disembarked in Italy illegally a
few days ago, and many thousands more are reportedly waiting to
come. They were driven from home by Turkish army campaigns against
Kurdish separatists and other local conflicts in southeastern
Turkey and northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Most of the refugees are seeking to reach families or friends
in countries with large Kurdish communities such as Germany,
France, the Netherlands and Sweden, and only see Italy as a
transfer station. Very few of them seek political asylum or
refugee status in Italy.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult for these people to be considered exiles or
political refugees because they don't declare themselves to be
such when they arrive in Italy," Dini said. He was also reacting
to some calls from government officials for them to be granted
refugee status.
</P>
<P>
Dini pointed out that the Kurds' arrival was often financed by
Kurds already resident in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The journey might cost as much as 7,000 dollars per person,
making it a highly profitable trade in which mafia in Italy,
Turkey, Albania and other countries are said to be involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Village Leaders Given Chance to Go to College </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 31 (Xinhua) -- "I can't believe I can go
to college; it's like a dream coming true," said Ma Lianglu, a
44-year-old village head in Youyilu Village in north China's Hebei
Province.
</P>
<P>
Ma is just one of 121 village heads who went to Hebei
Agriculture University to receive 1 1/2 years of college education
there. The village leaders are expected to take such courses as
law, economics, policy, agricultural technology and public
relations.
</P>
<P>
"For me, a diploma isn't important," Ma said. "I was worried a
little bit, before I came, whether what is taught here could help
my work; now I just feel it is very useful."
</P>
<P>
Several years ago his village was involved in a lasting lawsuit
and eventually lost because of dubious clauses in the signed
contract and a lack of legal knowledge. Ma learned a painful
lesson.
</P>
<P>
The law course Ma and fellow village leaders are taking will
make them better able to protect their villages' interests, an
official from the local organization department said.
</P>
<P>
The 121 village heads from 23 counties of Baoding city in the
province will go back to their posts after graduation.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to help raise the knowledge standard of the
whole village, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Baoding has drafted a three-year plan to educate the village
heads. By 1999, the people who have received college and
polytechnic school education will constitute 20 percent of all the
village leaders, a sharp increase over the present 1-to-2
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
