<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Radar Control System Operational at Beijing Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- A radar air-traffic control
system went into service Tuesday at the Capital Airport of
Beijing, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The state-of-the-art air-traffic control system, installed
initially in Beijing's Capital Airport as a replacement for the
out-of-date procedure-based system, indicates that China has taken
a major step towards keeping abreast with advanced technology in
the world's civil aviation sector," air traffic control officials
were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The system for the air terminal is expected to substantially
reduce time for take-offs and landings, improve the flight
punctuality rate and make better use of air space, said the
officials at yesterday's inauguration.
</P>
<P>
Advanced radar and accessories worth nearly 200 million yuan
(24.1 million US dollars) were imported from Italy, Norway and the
United States for installation at the Capital Airport, considered
as country's busiest airport.
</P>
<P>
Traffic at Capital Airport has been expanding by 12 percent a
year, according to bureau statistics. Aircraft arrivals and
departures are expected to exceed 140,000 in 1997, with a record
daily peak of 481 on September 1.
</P>
<P>
Procedure-based control or control with radar guidance has been
used for decades to supervise flights, mainly on the basis of
reports from air-traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
The system has been criticized for its low speed and
inaccuracy. Statistics indicates that cases of delayed flights
because of backward air-traffic control conditions exceeded 2,000
last year.
</P>
<P>
"With radar-based control air traffic system, the number of
planes allowed to land at or leave the Capital Airport during a
specified time period will double," said air traffic control
officials.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that radar-based air-traffic control system are
expected to be established at Guangzhou Baiyun Airport and
Shanghai Hongqiao Airport by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
