<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Storm Bank and End Hostage Siege </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Italy's hostage crisis ended
Tuesday morning after special assault police stormed a Milan bank
held up by a gunman for more than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
Italy's state television said two policemen were slightly
injured during the assault, while the gunman, Domenico Gargano,
was also hurt.
</P>
<P>
A 30-second television coverage showed that a trained guard dog
was unleashed and knocked Gargano down as he stepped outside the
bank.
</P>
<P>
Gargano opened fire as special agents jumped on and immobilized
him. Ricochets hurt two policemen and Gargano himself.
</P>
<P>
The three injured were taken to hospital after the operation,
the state television reported.
</P>
<P>
The crisis began when Sicilian-born Gargano, 35, pulled out a
gun and a hand grenade in the Banca Popolare di Milano branch,
Monday afternoon, apparently after being refused a loan of several
million lire.
</P>
<P>
He held four men in the bank as hostages and then released one
man to deliver his demand for 10 billion lire (5.7 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Early on Tuesday, police handed over four billion lire (2.3
million dollars) in return for the release of the bank's
manager. After further negotiations, two remaining hostages were
released in stages.
</P>
<P>
Gargano then demanded that police drive him to the city's main
square so that he could scatter the four billion lire to passers-by.
</P>
<P>
He planned to turn himself in at the court after scattering the
money, but police refused his demand and ended the crisis by the
raid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
