<HEADLINE> Russia, Japan Agree on Fishing Off Kuril Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Japan reached a
draft agreement Tuesday on fishing off the disputed Kuril islands,
after three-years of talks.
</P>
<P>
Russian chief negotiator Vasily Saplin said the two sides
agreed on quotas for Japanese fishermen, types of catches and time
limits for fishing.
</P>
<P>
He said that the agreement was expected to be signed by the
two governments in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
The southernmost islands in the Kuril chain, known as the
Northern Territories in Japan, were seized by Soviet troops at the
end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
At a summit in the Siberian city of Krasnoyarsk early last
month, Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto agreed to make joint efforts to reach an
agreement on fishery cooperation off the Kuril islands between the
two countries. 
</P>
