<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Expands Its Export-oriented Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province,
one of China's most developed areas, has scored overall growth in
foreign trade, overseas investment and technological cooperation
this year.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu, the third biggest foreign-trade base in China, handled
imports and exports of 20.2 billion U.S. dollars during the first
11 months of this year, a 21.93 percent rise over the same period
last year, with exports increasing 17.95 percent to nearly 13.96
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the provincial state-owned enterprises which are
authorized to directly handle foreign trade showed an increase of
19.61 percent during the same period, exceeding the provincial
average growth of foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
To attract more overseas funds, Jiangsu has invested more than
80 billion yuan (10 billion U.S. dollars) in the construction of
airports, highways and other basic facilities in the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province has approved 1,819 overseas
investment projects during the January-November period with
contractual funds of 7.694 billion U.S. dollars, ranking the first
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,819 projects, 213 are large projects involving
investments of more than 10 million U.S. dollars each. The
contractual investment of these large projects totaled 5.9 billion
U.S. dollars, accounting for 82.4 percent of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment in 11 state-level development zones --
including the Suzhou Industrial Park, a Sino-Singapore project;
Kunshan Economic and Technological Development Zone; and
Zhangjiagang Bonded Area -- has amounted to half the province's
total.
</P>
<P>
One hundred and seven overseas-funded enterprises have been
set up in the Suzhou Industrial Park, with a total investment
of 3.38 billion U.S. dollars. Of these enterprises, 77 are
high-tech industrial firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
