<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Encourage Development of Nongovernmental Economies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial center, will make greater efforts to develop
nongovernmental economies, including the private sector,
Vice-Mayor Chen Liangyu said at a meeting recently.
</P>
<P>
To become an international economic metropolis, Shanghai
needs an economic structure of multiform ownerships, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nongovernmental economies have come to account for 15 percent
of the city's industrial output value. In some suburban
counties, the private sector contributes one third of the
local revenues.
</P>
<P>
The city is leading China in developing foreign-funded
enterprises, which in 1996 provided one third of Shanghai's
exports and industrial and commercial taxes.
</P>
<P>
The nongovernmental sectors in the city have hired more than a
million people, alleviating the unemployment pressure, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will encourage nongovernmental economies to develop
high-tech industries and participate in the reform of state-run
enterprises in a bid to better use the huge amount of idle fixed
assets of the state-owned enterprises, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The city government will incorporate nongovernmental economies
into the outline of local economic and social development and
treat them as the state-owned sector, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that the city government will also work out various
policies and regulations to create an environment suitable for the
development of the nongovernmental economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
