<HEADLINE> "Amphibious Farmers" Emerging in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- More and more farmers in east
China have turned to aquatic breeding and pelagic fishing while still
staying on farming, and they are called "amphibious farmers" as a
result.
</P>
<P>
In Ganyu County in Jiangsu Province, for example, some 8,000
farmers have started the new business, as little farmland gives
them meagre income. A common approach in this regard is that the
farmers join local fishermen to shoulder risk and share profits.
</P>
<P>
In Liuxiang Town alone, some 3,000 farmers have bought shares
for purchasing large fishing boats with local fishermen. Another
2,000 farmers go fishing on the sea with fishermen, selling labor
as stocks.
</P>
<P>
In addition, about 3,000 farmers at Liuxiang have invested in
breeding prawns, crabs and shellfish. Of the 400 prawn growers in
the town, 95 percent are local farmers, working on 730 ha of water
surface. Some farmers have even gone to north and northeast China
provinces to raise prawns.
</P>
<P>
"Amphibious farmers" are also emerging in other
provinces of east China. They go back to their farmland in busy
farming seasons, while making extra money on the sea in slack
seasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
