<HEADLINE> Anand Beats Adams to Meet Karpov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRONINGEN, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Viswanathan Anand of India
beat England's Michael Adams here on Tuesday to meet Anatoly
Karpov in the final of the World Chess Championship.
</P>
<P>
He defeated Adams after 65 moves in a sudden-death blitz game
after the two grandmasters drew all their previous eight games.
</P>
<P>
Anand, playing white pieces, had only four minutes while Adams
five with black.
</P>
<P>
Anand managed to push up a threatening c-pawn to c6 despite
Adams' accurate defensive contortions.
</P>
<P>
The Indian gave up a pawn on move 37 but staged a subsequent
attack which won him back two.
</P>
<P>
With the c-pawn now just one square from queening, Adams had to
use knight, bishop and rook to hold it back while Anand's powerful
bishop pair dominated the board.
</P>
<P>
The blitz tiebreaker was preceded Tuesday by a tiebreaker of
two 25-minute-per-player games and two 15-minute games, all ended
in draw, after the pair drew four straight normal-speed games on
successive days.
</P>
<P>
Anand will challenge Anatoly Karpov of Russia in a six-game
contest for the International Chess Federation world championship
in Lausanne, Switzerland from January 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
