<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador's Shrimp Production Gets Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's exports of shrimp rose
in 1997 by 26 percent in volume and 39 percent in value compared
with those in 1996, hitting a historic record,the Chamber of
Aquiculture reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign sales of the crustacean amounted to 106,221 tons worth
858.58 million U.S. dollars in the year. 95 percent of the total
was shrimp cultivated and the rest was fished.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino climatic phenomenon is affecting seriously the
fishing of shrimp, but the event is favorable for the cultivation
in pools, as the rising temperature of waters fosters the growth
of the species, explained the Chairman of the Chamber, Erick
Notarianni.
</P>
<P>
He added that higher temperature accelerates the shrimp's
metabolism and lowers the salt level of the pool's waters.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador ranks second in production of shrimp in the world, just
after Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The South American country counts on 180,000 hectares for the
raising of shrimp and more than 100,000 workers in the aquiculture
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Arranges Friendly With Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria will play Argentina in
a friendly to warm up for the 1998 soccer World Cup finals,
according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, who beat defending champions Germany on their way to
the 1994 World Cup semi-finals, will meet Argentina on March 11.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria has been drawn with Paraguay, Spain and Nigeria in
Group D of the World Cup finals next Summer.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, which won the World Cup in 1978 and 1986, is in
Group H with Croatia, Jamaica and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
