<HEADLINE> Belgian Court Sticks to Tobacco Ban Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- A Belgian local court said
Tuesday it did not have the power to overrule a government ban on
tobacco advertising in sports events.
</P>
<P>
The court decision came just before the December 31 deadline
set by Formula One chief Bernie Ecclestone who gave Belgian Grand
Prix organizers some time to find a way around the government ban.
</P>
<P>
The law, which bans all tobacco advertising and sponsorship
from January 1999 in Belgium, was challenged by supporters of the
Belgian Formula One race at Spa-Francorchamps.
</P>
<P>
These supporters include local organizers, retailers and
government authorities.
</P>
<P>
After the Verviers court announced its decision, legal
representatives of the race organizers and local restaurants,
cafes and tourism agencies said that they would take the case to
Belgium's appeal court, the highest court on legal and
administrative matters in the country.
</P>
<P>
A lifting of the Belgian ban law may allow local race
organizers to continue their races until 2006 when the European
Union decides to launch a union-wide complete ban on tobacco
advertising and sponsorship in sports and arts activities.
</P>
<P>
An EU-wide ban on tobacco advertising and sponsorship will lead
the tobacco industry to support major events outside the EU. Now
over 70 percent of the world television audience of Formula One
races is in the Asia-Pacific region though 10 of the 16 annual
Formula One championship races are held in EU countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
