<HEADLINE> Thailand Asks for Suspending Purchase of Fighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States will
consult with Thailand for its request to suspend the purchase of a
squadron of U.S.-built F/A-18 Hornet fighter jets because of
economic woes, the Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
"We are consulting with the Thai government on this issue,"
Pentagon spokesman Maj. Bryan Salas told reporters.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Air Chief Marshal Thananit Niamchan, commander of
the Royal Thai Air Force, said Thailand would negotiate with
Boeing Co. to delay the scheduled eight aircraft purchase for
three years. And he will lead a team to negotiate with Boeing next
month for the deal, valued at 392.1 million dollars, originally to
be completed by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Salas declined to comment on any role the Pentagon might play
in the coming Thai talks with Boeing, but he said, "The U.S.
security commitment to Thailand remains strong during this time of
economic turmoil."
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for Boeing said the company had not yet received
official notification of the Thai request for the delay from the
U.S. navy, which is handling the contract through the U.S. foreign
military sales program.
</P>
<P>
"Until we've received official work, there's nothing we can say
or do," she said.
</P>
<P>
Sources said Boeing Co. is expected to charge Thailand about 9
percent of the total project value, or 26 million dollars, for
delaying payment and delivery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
