<HEADLINE> U.S. Helicopters Rescue Sinking British Ship Crew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Air Force and Coast
Guard helicopters rescued all 28 crewmen of a British-owned cargo
ship that were sinking in Atlantic Ocean off Florida.
</P>
<P>
The 28 men jumped into the chilly waters to be hoisted on to
the helicopters as winds made it impossible to lift them from the
ship's deck.
</P>
<P>
The 493-foot (160-meter) Merchant Patriot began sinking this
morning 270 miles (435 km) east of Cape Canaveral, Florida, after
a water pipe ruptured in the engine room and flooded the vessel.
</P>
<P>
The ship, owned by the British company Cenergo Navigation Ltd.,
was traveling from Praia Mole, Brazil, to Savannah, Georgia, with
general cargo including containers and heavy steel.
</P>
<P>
Five U.S. Air Force and Coast Guard helicopters from bases in
Florida and the Bahamas joined the rescue mission. The crewmen
were plucked from the sea one by one by rescue crewmen lowered
down in a basket as strong wind blew the life raft off the
vessel's stern.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters flew the rescued crewmen to Marsh Harbor on
Great Abaco Island, Bahamas, about 25 miles (40 kilometers) away.
They were reported to be in good health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
