<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Population of 74 Poor Countries will Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The population boom is
still booming in the world's poorest countries and 74 less
developed nations can expect their populations to double in 30
years or less, the Population Institute reported today.
</P>
<P>
In its annual overview report, the Washington-based institute
said the world's total population will reach six billion by
mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
"Rapid population growth in the poorest countries of the world
remains the most pressing global demographic problem, despite a
decline in annual increments in human numbers," the institute's
president Werner Fornos told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Fornos disputed recent reports, notably in the New York Times
magazine and the Wall Street Journal, which said that the global
population boom had ended or there may even be a "population
implosion".
</P>
<P>
Such reports "ignore demographic realities", he said, citing
figures from the U.N. Food and Agricultural Organization listing
86 countries as low-income and food-deficient, and suggesting this
is attributable to overpopulation in those countries.
</P>
<P>
"Although many of the countries of Latin America and Asia have
recorded significant fertility declines, the annual number of
births worldwide will be at least 132 million increase for many
more years to come," he added.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 percent of the world's population now resides in the
developing world. The population growth is slowing down in the
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
In Mexico, Morocco, Turkey, Bangladesh, Indonesia, Kenya,
Brazil, the Philippines, Egypt and Pakistan, the use of
contraception has cut fertility rates since 1973, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The institute, a nonprofit, nonpartisan organization that seeks
a balance among the world's population, environment and resources,
called for increased contributions from the developed world,
including the United States.
</P>
<P>
Fornos complained Washington has cut population assistance over
the last four years from 585 million to 385 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971231.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Continues Advance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street
extended their gains today, lifting the Dow Jones industrial
average back toward 8,000 points with just one session left in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average, up 113.10 Monday, gained an
additional 123.56 points, or 1.6 percent, in active trading today
to close at 7,915.97. Broad market indicators also rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by nearly a 3-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 498.97 million
shares as against 441.25 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 17.49 to 970.84,
moving within 13 points of record territory. The NYSE composite
index rose 8.79 to 510.28, about 4 points from a new closing high.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 27.58 to 1,565.03, the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 9.62 to 678.91, and the
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 7.34 to 434.01.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index boosted this year's increase to
31 percent and the Nasdaq composite index increased its 1997 gain
to 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
Both Dow and the S&AMP;P 500 have posted better-than 20 percent
gains for three straight years. They have more than doubled over
that span.
</P>
<P>
Long-term interest rates in the bond market rose back toward 6
percent after a report showing that consumer confidence jumped to
a 28-year high in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
