<HEADLINE> Kinkel: 1997 Is a Successful Year for European Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 30 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel Tuesday struck a positive balance of the year 1997,
describing it as "an extremely successful year for European
foreign and security politics".
</P>
<P>
In his New Year's statement delivered today, Kinkel noted that
during the course of 1997, European and transatlantic institutions
had managed to make considerable progress in shaping Europe for
the 21st century. Major achievements made during the year
including:
</P>
<P>
-- The signing of the European Union Amsterdam Treaty, which
has modernized the organization and created the preconditions for
admitting new members;
</P>
<P>
-- The creation of a strategic partnership between Russia and
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), which has filled up
security trenches in Europe;
</P>
<P>
-- The historic decisions to enlarge the EU and the NATO, which
have laid the foundation for a new European security order.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 also saw EU states make serious preparations for
the planned single European currency, the Euro, Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
"Although decisions on Euro member states are still due to be
made in May next year, it is already foreseeable that a large
number of EU countries, including Germany and France, will qualify
for the first wave," Kinkel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
